Benton County.—Population, 1910, 12,452; 1900, 11,888. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $1,456,210. Average assessed value of land, $4.17. Area, 412 square miles. Railway mileage, 26. This county is bounded on the east by the Tennessee River. Portions of the county are well timbered. The surface is level and generally fertile. This is one of the peanut-growing counties of the State, and other products are corn, wheat, oats, vegetables, and live stock. The county is intersected by the Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railway. Camden, the county seat, has a population of 700, and is on the Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railway. It has good schools, churches, a weekly newspaper, and a number of flourishing mercantile establishments and a bank. Information will be furnished by G. M. Leslie, Immigration Bureau, Camden.
Carroll County.—Population, 1910, 23,971; 1900, 24,250. Assessed val-
Average assessed value of land, Area, 600 square miles. Railway mileage, 68. Drained by the
Surface generally level, and there is con-Corn, cotton, wheat, fruits, and hogs are the staple products. Fruit-growing and poultry-raising are profitable industries. Huntingdon, the county seat, has a population of 1,500, and is on the N., C. & St. L. Railway. The town has good public and private schools, two newspapers, waterworks, electric lights, good churches, and flourishing manufacturing and commercial establishments. McKenzie, another flourishing town, is on the Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railway and the Louisville & Nashville Railroad, and is noted for its schools. It has a bank, a. weekly newspaper, and numerous mercantile establishments. Truck-growing is largely and profitably engaged in in Carroll County. Information will be furnished by Garver & Garver, Huntingdon.
Chester County.—Population, 1910, 9,090; 1900, 9,896. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $1,279,990. Average assessed value of land, $5.30. Area, 288 square miles. Railway mileage, 10. This county is on the highlands of West Tennessee, and is drained by the Forked Deer River and intersected by the Mobile & Ohio Railroad. The soil is sandy and very fertile. Cotton is the leading staple, but other crops are profitably grown. . Henderson, the county seat, is on the Mobile & Ohio Railroad, and has a population of 1,100. It has a weekly newspaper, banks, splendid schools and churches, several manufacturing establishments,,and prosperous stores. Information will be furnished by J. T. Rogers, County Immigration Bureau, Chester.
Crockett County.
valuation of taxable property, $2,024,040. Average assessed value of land, $9.40. Area, 275 square miles. Railway mileage, 12. Drained by the Forked Deer River and well timbered in portions of the county. The soil in the eastern portion is sandy loam and clay and well adapted to the growing of vegetables and fruits. The western portion is level and rich, and is well adapted to the growing of wheat, corn, potatoes, and grasses. Alamo, the county seat, has a population of 500, and is six miles from the L. & N. Railroad. It has a weekly newspaper, a bank, churches, schools, and several manufacturing establishments. Bells, the largest town in the county, has a population of 800, and is 70 miles from Memphis on the L. & N. Railroad. It has schools, churches, a newspaper, stores, and manufacturing establishments. Other towns are Gadsden, Crockett Mills, and Maury City. Information will be furnished by Alamo Real Estate and Trust Company, Alamo.
Decatur County.
valuation of taxable property, $1,096,700. Average assessed value of land, $4.10. Area, 310 square miles. Railway mileage, 11. Bounded on the east and south by the Tennessee River, the surface is comparatively level and is covered with a fine growth of timber. Fine iron ore is found in this county. Phosphate deposits are also found, as are marble and granite. Corn, cotton, and hogs are staple products. Decaturville, the county seat, has a population of 400, and is five miles from the Tennessee River and the same distance from the N., C. & St. L. Railway. It has churches, schools, stores, a weekly newspaper, and a bank. Parsons is the principal business point in the county on the railroad. Information will be furnished by County Immigration Bureau, Decaturville.
Dyer County.—Population, 1910, 27,721; 1900, 23,776. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $5,674,775. Average assessed value of land, $11.90. Area, 495 square miles. Railway mileage, 58. This county is bounded on the west by the Mississippi River, and is well watered by smaller streams. It is hilly, rolling, and level, and is one of the most
land, $4.10. Area, 550 square miles. Railway mileage, 42. Drained by the Hatchie River and affluents of the Tennessee. Part of the 'county is level, and in some portions there is a fine growth of timber. The staple products are cotton, corn, and hogs. The Mobile & Ohio and the Southern Railway traverse the county. Selmer, the county seat, is on the M. & O. Railroad, 35 miles south of Jackson. It has a bank, weekly newspapers, good schools and churches, manufacturing and mercantile establishments. Adamsville and Stantonville are other towns in the county. Address William Lea, Immigration Bureau, Selmer.
Obion County.—Population, 1910, 29,946; 1900, 28,286. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $8,468,459. Average assessed value of land, $16.50. Area, 540 square miles. This county is bounded on the north by Kentucky and on the west by Reelfoot Lake, and is one of the richest agricultural counties in the State. Its surface is nearly level, and there is a plentiful supply of timber. The soil is rich and fertile, and wheat, corn, oats, cotton, and live stock are the staple products. It is one of the best wheat-producing counties in the State. It is intersected by the Illinois Central, the Mobile & Ohio, and the Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railroads. Union City, the county seat, has a population of about 4,500, and is located at the junction of these railroads. It has splendid churches, good schools, banks, weekly newspapers, lumber mills, railroad shops, and other manufacturing establishments. For further information address Carter & White, Union City.
Shelby County.—Population, 1910, 191,439; 1900, 153,557. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $82,244,022. Average assessed value of land, $24.80. Area, 728 square miles. Railway mileage, 208. This county is bounded on the west by the Mississippi River, on the &outn by the State of Mississippi, and is intersected by the Loosahatchie and Wolf Rivers. Its surface is level, and portions are well timbered. The soil is very rich and fertile, and it is one of the best cotton-producing counties in the State. The staple products are cotton, corn, lumber, and hogs. Market-gardening is carried on extensively. Memphis, the county seat and the largest city In the State, has a population of 131,105, is located on the Mississippi River, and numerous railroads enter the city. A fine bridge crosses the Mississippi at this point. It has an excellent system of streets and sewers. It is a great manufacturing city, and its shipping facilities have made it one of the most important marts in the United States. It is the leading cotton market of the South, and is also a leading lumber market and a central market for mules and horses. It is the center of the cotton seed oil industry in the South and the largest cotton seed oil market in the world. It is a rapidly growing city, and its importance as a manufacturing and distributing point is growing. The West Tennessee Normal School is located at this point, and the city and county made large donations for its establishment. Address Business Men’s Club, Memphis.
Tipton County.—Population, 1910, 29,459; 1900, 29,273. Assessed val-• uation of taxable property, $3,053,240. Average assessed value of land, $7.90. Area, 400 square miles. Railway mileage, 27. This county is bounded on the west by the Mississippi River, and the surface is level except for a range of hills near the river. The county is well timbered, and it is well watered by running streams and artesian wells. The soil is rich; and cotton, corn, wheat, oats, fruits, vegetables, and live stock are the products. The Louisville & Nashville and the Illinois Central Railroads traverse the county. Covington, the county seat, has a population of 2,000, and is 38 miles from Memphis on the I. C. Railroad. It has fine churches, banks, two weekly newspapers, electric lights, waterworks, a cotton mill, cotton seed oil mill, and other manufacturing enterprises, and is a live, progressive town. Address W. F. Bringle, <• County Immigration Bureau, Covington.
Weakley County.—Population, 1910, 31,929; 1900, 32,546. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $6,576,247. Average assessed value of land, $11.60. Area, 620 square miles. Railway mileage, 51. This county is intersected by the Obion River, and the surface is generally level, with a good growth of timber in some portions. The soil is very fertile, and the staple products are cotton, tobacco, corn, wheat, oats, fruits, vegetables, and live stock. The Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railway and the Illinois Central Railroad traverse the county. Dresden, the county seat, with a population of 800, has good schools, churches, lumber mills, a stave factory, a tannery, a bank, and a weekly newspaper. Martin, another prosperous town, has a population of 2,300, and is located at the junction of the railroads. It has many business establishments, good schools and churches, manufacturing establishments, and newspapers. Address M. D. Brassfield, County Immigration Bureau, Dresden, Tenn.

Trenton, the county seat, has a population of 2,500, and is on the Forked Deer River and Mobile & Ohio Railroad. It has a number of manufacturing establishments, a weekly newspaper, good schools and churches, banks, and mercantile establishments. Humboldt, another prosperous town, has a population of 3,500, is the center of the truck-growing industry of West Tennessee, and is also a manufacturing town, with excellent school facilities, churches, a bank, weekly newspaper, and flourishing mercantile establishments. It is at the junction of the Mobile & Ohio and Louisville & Nashville Railroads. Milan, another prosperous town, has a population of 1,700. It is at the junction of the Illinois Central and Louisville & Nashville Railroads, and is a vegetable and fruit shipping point. Other prosperous towns in this county are Dyer, Fruitland, Rutherford, and Medina. For information address G. W. Wade, County Immigration Bureau, Trenton.
Hardeman County.—Population, 1910, 23,011; 1900, 22,976. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $2,999,773. Average assessed value of land, $4.95. Area, 640 square miles. Railway mileage, 73. This county borders on Mississippi, and is drained by the Big Hatchie River. Its surface is nearly level and in many sections covered with fine timber. The soil is fertile, and it is one of the best cotton-producing counties in the State. Other staples are corn, hay, and timber. The county is traversed by the Illinois Central, the Southern, and the Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railroads. Bolivar, the county seat, has a population of 1,100, and is on the Big Hatchie River and the Illinois Central Railroad 18 miles south of Jackson. It has good schools and churches, a weekly newspaper, and banks. For information address County Immigration Bureau, Bolivar.
Hardin County.—Population, 1910, 17,521; 1900, 19,246. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $2,490,105. Average assessed value of land, $5.25. Area, 587 square miles. Railway mileage, none. This county borders on Alabama and Mississippi, and is intersected by the Tennessee River, which passes through the county and is navigable the year round. The western portion is generally level, while the eastern portion is hilly, with fertile valleys. The eastern part is well timbered. The staple products are cotton, corn, and live stock. Savannah,* the county seat, has a population of 1,800, and has excellent public and private schools, churches, and mercantile establishments and a weekly newspaper. Congress has established a national park at Shiloh, the scene of a bloody battle during the Civil War. Information will be furnished by County Immigration Bureau, Savannah.

Madison County.—Population, 1910, 39,357; 1900, 36,333. Assessed valuation of taxable property, $7,069,471. Average assessed value of land, $7.30. Area, 520 square miles. Railway mileage, 90. Its surface is generally level, and it is intersected by the Forked Deer River. The soil is very fertile; and the staple products are corn, cotton, fruits, vegetables, and live stock. The Illinois Central, the Mobile & Ohio, and the Nashville, Chattanooga & St. Louis Railroads traverse the county. A - large cotton-manufacturing establishment is located at Bemls. Jack-son, the county seat, has a population of 16,000 and all the conveniences that go to make a modern city. An artesian waterworks system, owned by the city, supplies the residents with pure water. Jackson has fine public and private schools, and is noted as an educational center. It has enterprising daily and weekly newspapers and other periodicals. Address Commercial Association, Jackson.

OF THE TENNESSEE RIVER, FOR THE USE OF THE MISSISSIPPI SQUADRON, ONDER COMMAND OF ACTING REAR ADMIRAL S. P. LEE, U. S. N., From Reconnaissance by a party of the United States Coast Survey. A. D. BACHE, Supt. This Reconnaissance of the Tennessee River, from Paducah, Kentucky, to Florence, Alabama, comprising a distance of 255 miles, was made by Assistant F. H. Ghrdks, and his party, at the request of Admiral Lee. It is based upon determinations of latitude and longitude made by means of an eight-inch vertical circle and two chronometers; the differences of longitude being referred to Cairo. The following positions on the Tennessee River were thus determined: NO. STATION. LATITUDE. . LONOITUUE. East of Cairo, Ill. MAGNETIC OECEINATION. East. O / // O / n O / 1 Paducah, Ky 37 04 35 0 34 29 6 47 2 Pattersons Landing, Ky. . . . 37 03 12 0 46 07 6 45 3 Twenty-seven Mile Island, Ky. . . 36 57 14 0 56 51 7 19 4 Fort Henry, Tenn 36 30 23 1 07 35 6 20 5 Johnsonville, Tenn 36 03 48 1 11 29 5 47 6 Clifton, Tenn 35 23 17 1 10 07 5 45 7 Clifton Presbyterian Ckutch, Tenn. 35 23 07 1 10 10 - — 8 Chickasaw, near Eastport, Miss. . . 34 53 30 1 04 47 .... 9 Florence Bridge, Ala 34 47 15 1 29 26 5 20 The average uncertainty in these results is, for latitude, al^^Bme second of arc; and for longitude, within one second in time. • The intermediate points between the stations were laidState, County, and Land Office maps, the distances being verified or correcteflMPnnformation obtained of the most reliable pilots on the river, and from the rate of-the steamer used for the Reconnaissance. This rate had been closely ascertained, and the results of several trips proved satisfactory. All the courses of the river were traced by compass observations, the variation of the magnetic needle having been determined by the party at seven of the stations named in the table above. The habitations, the different cultivations, bluffs, hills, creeks and bayous, landings and ferries, were plotted as nearly as possible in their true positions on the map. The soundings on the bars and shoals of the river were taken on the 21st and 22d of June, 1865, at a so-called 8-feet stage of water. The stages of water in the Tennessee may be divided into low ordinary, and high water. A low stage of water prevails, under usual circumstances, for three months of the year; a medium or ordinary stage lasts, generally, five months, and a high stage four months. The average depth of the river at a low stage is, on all the bars, = 3* feet, excepting Duck River shoal and Big Bend shoals, on which 6 inches less is found at such a stage. This applies, however, only to the river below Chickasaw. The average depth at a medium stage may be considered 9 feet on the bars. At this stage only the Green Bottom bar is bare. The following coincidences are always noticed at certain stages of the river: ♦ • 1. With 4 feet on Duck River bar there are 4* feet of water on Twenty-seven Mile Island bar. 2. When the river is at a 4-feet stage the Pentecost Tow-head is bare for 75 feet in breadth from the left bank. 3. McCulloch’s bar, above Hodge Spring branch, is bare at a river stage of 2*- feet. 4. Saltpetre Bluff bar becomes visible at a stage of 5 feet. 5. Cedar Creek bar is also bare at a 5-feet stage. 6. The Buffalo shoals, above the Decatur Furnace, show at a river stage of 26 inches. OF THE TENNESSEE RIVER, FOR THE USE OF THE MISSISSIPPI SQUADRON, ONDER COMMAND OF ACTING REAR ADMIRAL S. P. LEE, U. S. N., From Reconnaissance by a party of the United States Coast Survey. A. D. BACHE, Supt. This Reconnaissance of the Tennessee River, from Paducah, Kentucky, to Florence, Alabama, comprising a distance of 255 miles, was made by Assistant F. H. Ghrdks, and his party, at the request of Admiral Lee. It is based upon determinations of latitude and longitude made by means of an eight-inch vertical circle and two chronometers; the differences of longitude being referred to Cairo. The following positions on the Tennessee River were thus determined: NO. STATION. LATITUDE. . LONOITUUE. East of Cairo, Ill. MAGNETIC OECEINATION. East. O / // O / n O / 1 Paducah, Ky 37 04 35 0 34 29 6 47 2 Pattersons Landing, Ky. . . . 37 03 12 0 46 07 6 45 3 Twenty-seven Mile Island, Ky. . . 36 57 14 0 56 51 7 19 4 Fort Henry, Tenn 36 30 23 1 07 35 6 20 5 Johnsonville, Tenn 36 03 48 1 11 29 5 47 6 Clifton, Tenn 35 23 17 1 10 07 5 45 7 Clifton Presbyterian Ckutch, Tenn. 35 23 07 1 10 10 - — 8 Chickasaw, near Eastport, Miss. . . 34 53 30 1 04 47 .... 9 Florence Bridge, Ala 34 47 15 1 29 26 5 20 The average uncertainty in these results is, for latitude, al^^Bme second of arc; and for longitude, within one second in time. • The intermediate points between the stations were laidState, County, and Land Office maps, the distances being verified or correcteflMPnnformation obtained of the most reliable pilots on the river, and from the rate of-the steamer used for the Reconnaissance. This rate had been closely ascertained, and the results of several trips proved satisfactory. All the courses of the river were traced by compass observations, the variation of the magnetic needle having been determined by the party at seven of the stations named in the table above. The habitations, the different cultivations, bluffs, hills, creeks and bayous, landings and ferries, were plotted as nearly as possible in their true positions on the map. The soundings on the bars and shoals of the river were taken on the 21st and 22d of June, 1865, at a so-called 8-feet stage of water. The stages of water in the Tennessee may be divided into low ordinary, and high water. A low stage of water prevails, under usual circumstances, for three months of the year; a medium or ordinary stage lasts, generally, five months, and a high stage four months. The average depth of the river at a low stage is, on all the bars, = 3* feet, excepting Duck River shoal and Big Bend shoals, on which 6 inches less is found at such a stage. This applies, however, only to the river below Chickasaw. The average depth at a medium stage may be considered 9 feet on the bars. At this stage only the Green Bottom bar is bare. The following coincidences are always noticed at certain stages of the river: ♦ • 1. With 4 feet on Duck River bar there are 4* feet of water on Twenty-seven Mile Island bar. 2. When the river is at a 4-feet stage the Pentecost Tow-head is bare for 75 feet in breadth from the left bank. 3. McCulloch’s bar, above Hodge Spring branch, is bare at a river stage of 2*- feet. 4. Saltpetre Bluff bar becomes visible at a stage of 5 feet. 5. Cedar Creek bar is also bare at a 5-feet stage. 6. The Buffalo shoals, above the Decatur Furnace, show at a river stage of 26 inches. Points of Interest in West Virginia
HARPERS FERRY—Scene of J.ohn Brown’s attempt to free the slaves. Meeting place of Potomac and Shenandoah rivers. Spectacular scenery. In Jefferson County, on State Route No. 50.
CHARLES TOWN—Where John Brown was tried and hanged. Also former home of several relatives of George Washington. In Jefferson County, at intersection of State Routes No. 49 and No. 50.
SHEPHERDSTOWN—Oldest town in West Virginia. Where James Rumsey invented the first steamboat and tested it on the Potomac. In Jefferson County, on State Route No. 48.
MARTINSBURG—Chief city of the great West Virginia fruit region and home of nationally-known knitting mills. In Berkeley County, at intersection of U. S. Highway No. 11, and State Routes No. 47 and No. 49.
BERKELEY SPRINGS—State park here contains springs with remarkable medicinal powers, gift of Lord Fairfax to Colony of Virginia. Central point of agricultural region producing especially fine tomatoes. In Morgan County at intersection of State Routes No. 9 and No. 47.
POINT PLEASANT — Scene of historic battle Oct. 10, 1774. Commemorated by towering monument and State park. Old Indian smoke signal point near by. Indian Chief Cornstalk, and “Mad Anne” Bailey, heroine of pioneer days, buried here. On the Ohio, at mouth of the Great Kanawha. One of finest river views in State. In Mason County. At intersection of State Routes No. 19 and No. 62.
MARLINTON—Many historic associations. Site of old Fort Greenbrier. General Lee said to have spent first night under canvas here at beginning of Civil War. Associated with many bloody fights between Indians and settlers. Old Warrior's Road, an Indian trail, may still be plainly seen. Magnificent scenic region. At intersection of State Routes No. 24 and No. 43 in Pocahontas County. (No. 24 is Seneca Trail.)
BLENNERHASSETT ISLAND—In the Ohio river, within sight of Parkersburg. Where Aaron Burr plotted to form a Southwestern empire.
Points of Interest in West Virginia
CLARKSBURG—Important manufacturing and commercial city. Birthplace of “Stonewall’’ Jackson. Center of large coal and chemical industries. In Harrison County, at intersection of U S. 50, U. S. 19, and State No. 22.
CHEAT RIVER REGION—In Monongalia, Preston, and Tucker Counties. Highlands and gorges, forests and rushing waters. Profusion of scenic views. Reached over U. S. No. 50, State Route No. 7, and their tributary roads.
MORGANTOWN—Home of West Virginia University. Half-million-dollar stadium seating 32,000 recently completed. Progressive manufacturing city. In Monongalia County at intersection of U. S. 19, U. S. 119, State Route No. 7, and State Route No. 73.
FAIRMONT—Vigorous manufacturing city. A central point in big Monongahela Valley coal field. At intersection or U. S. No. 19, State Route No. 6 and State No. 73. In Marion County.
FALLS OF TYGART VALLEY RIVER—Between Fairmont and Grafton. Series of cascades and rapids a mile in length. Near State Route No. 6.
GRAFTON—Important railroad town. Has State's only National soldiers’ cemetery. Childhood home of Anna Jarvis, founder of Mother’s Day. In Taylor County, at intersection of U. S. 50 and State No. 56.
PHILIPPI—Home of Broaddus College. Scene of first inland battle of Civil War. In Barbour County at intersection of State Routes No. 5 6 and No. 69.
STATE FOUR-H CAMP—At Jackson’s Mill, the boyhood home of “Stonewall’’ Jackson, to whom it is a memorial. Maintained by the State as a training school for farm boys and girls, in all the various phases of farm life, and in all the things that go to make good citizens. Open all the year. In Lewis County, a few miles north of Weston, reached via U. S. 19 and paved county road.
STATE GAME FARM—A preserve for native wild animals. In Upshur County. On State Route No. 22, just south of French Creek.
WEBSTER, SPRINGS—Scenic summer resort. In midst of spectacular mountains and forests. In Webster County, at intersection of State Routes 15 and 22.
Points of Interest in West Virginia
ELKINS—Home of Davis and Elkins College. Beautifully situated. In Randolph County, at intersection of State Routes No. 53, No. 56, and No. 5 8. In good lumber, coal, and cattle territory.
BIRTHPLACE OF ABRAHAM LINCOLN’S MOTHER—It has been definitely established that Nancy Hanks was born near Burlington, Mineral County, West Virginia. On U. S. Highway No. 50.
CHARLESTON—Capital city of West Virginia. Beautifully situated modern metropolis. Manufacturing and commercial center. Chief city of world’s greatest bituminous coal region. Mammoth axe and sheet glass factories. U. S. Government armor plate plant. Chemical plants of DuPont interests and numerous others. In Kanawha County. At intersection of U. S. No. 60, U. S. No. 21, State Route No. 2 and State Route No. 19.
STATE MUSEUM AT CHARLESTON (in City Library Building, Lee Street). Some of the more important objects of interest:
Large collection of Indian implements; relics of pioneer times; relics of all our wars; Civil and World War flags; a Daniel Boone collection; the rifle of Lewis Wetzel, the Indian scout; the desk of John Beckley, first Clerk of the Continental Congress, at which some of the signers of the Declaration of Independence are said to have affixed their signatures to that immortal document; a model of Rumsey’s steamboat, and a model of the Blennerhassett Mansion.
WORLD’S GREATEST BITUMINOUS COAL FIELD—Along and south of U. S. No. 60 in West V irginia lie the most extensive deposits of bituminous coal on earth. Much of it is the high grade smokeless coal. The total is estimated to be sufficient, at the present rate of production, to last 2,000 years, and is valued at six hundred billion dollars. Greater part of this land was once owned by Robert Morris, who financed the American Revolution. Penetrated by several roads branching off from U. S. No. 60. Chief city next to Charleston is Bluefield. Important cities and towns include Beckley, Logan, Welch, Williamson, Hinton, Princeton, Fayetteville, Pineville, Wayne, Madison, Hamlin, Matoaka, Northfork, Kimball, Oak Hill. Mt. Hope, Montgomery, Whitesville, Mullens, Sharpies, Glen Rogers, Eccles, and scores of others.
Points of Interest in West Virginia
SOUTH BRANCH OF POTOMAC and NATIONAL PARKS REGION—This great scenic area includes portions of several counties in the northeastern part of the State. With more than 400 miles of trout streams, an abundance of wild game, and innumerable ideal camping spots, all in the midst of magnificent mountain scenery, it forms a veritable paradise for the vacationist or the sportsman. Almost all of the Monongahela National Forest lies in West Virginia, covering parts of Tucker, Randolph, Grant, Pocahontas, and Pendleton Counties. A part of the Shenandoah National Forest lies in Hardy, Pendleton, and Hampshire counties, extending eastward into Virginia These forests are guarded by Government rangers, lookouts, and patrolmen. There is an excellent system of forest trails connecting with State roads, and telephone communication is readily available.
No permit is required for a temporary camp in a National Forest. All campers are required to be careful about fire. The State laws apply to hunting and fishing, and may be obtained from the State Game and Fish Commission, Charleston, W. Va.
The main road penetrating this region is State Route No. 28, hard surfaced all the way from its intersection with U. S. 50, through Hampshire, Hardy, Grant, and Pendleton Counties, to Franklin. It has numerous tributary roads which are excellent in summer and fall.
A few of the many features of the region are;
East Seneca Ridge, including “Seneca Rocks,” and Miley Gap—a vertical stratum of quartzite of flinty hardness, extending across part of Grant and all of Pendleton County. Where visible, the top is seen against the sky line like a notched knife blade. The beautiful cliffs known as “Seneca Rocks” are on the North Fork, at the mouth of Seneca Creek, along State Route No. 53, in Pendleton County. Four miles belo\y is seen Miley Gap, where two parallel sheets of quartzite rise vertically like a slender spire 600 feet toward the sky. The varied coloring of the quartzite adds greatly to its attractiveness.
“Smoke Hole” is a canoe-shaped valley north of Upper Tract in Pendleton County, through which flows the South Branch. It is conveniently reached from State Route No. 28.
MOUNT HOPE—West Va., situated midway between Charleston and Bluefield, on the Lakes to Florida Highway, founded 1 889, destroyed by fire March 24, 1910, presents one of the most thriving little cities in the State of West Virginia. Population about 5000. Altitude approximately 1900 feet. Good schools, all main thoroughfares paved, modern and well equipped paid fire department, good churches, and the heart and distributing center of the New River Coal Fields. Sulphur water of medicinal quality is found in abundance.
Points of Interest in West Virginia
HUNTINGTON—One of State's largest cities, and one of chief manufacturing and commercial centers. Has 156 manufacturing plants, making wide variety of products of steel, glass, nickel, and wood. Railroad gateway for millions of tons of coal. Big tobacco market. New million dollar bridge spans Ohio river connecting roads of West Virginia and Ohio. At intersection of U. S. No. 60, U. S. No. 52, and State Routes No. 8, No 10, and No. 62.
ICE MOUNTAIN—A natural refrigerator containing ice even on the hottest days. This phenomenon is in the eastern part of Hampshire County, about half a mile from North River Mills. At the base of a mountain along North River, for a space 200 yards long and 35 feet wide, ice in large quantities is found throughout the year. It lies between U. S. 50 and State Route No. 9.
ORGAN CAVE—Large cave with _ passageways improved and lighted for about a mile. Used by Confederate forces for manufacture of saltpetre during war. Takes name from organ pipe formation of stalactites. Many other interesting formations. In Greenbrier County, near boundary of Monroe County. Near State Route No. 24.
WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS—Nationally famous resort for more than one hundred years. First summer White House still standing. A favorite spot of prominent men and women. Palatial hotels and wide variety of indoor and outdoor recreation. In Greenbrier County on U. S. No. 60.
CANAAN VALLEY and BLACKWATER FALLS -A magnificent valley lying in an oval, surrounded
by a ridge of hills. The falls of the Blackwater river in this valley, are considered among the most beautiful the state. In northeastern corner of Tucker
in
County, reached from State Routes No. 58 and No. 40.
CAPON SPRINGS—Natural mineral springs with same analysis as those of Carlsbad. Visited by Daniel Webster, President Pierce and other noted men. In southeastern corner of Hampshire County, near State Route No. 23.
SPRUCE KNOB—Highest point in State. In southwestern corner of Pendleton County. It is 4.860 feet above sea level. Harper’s Ferry, 260 feet, is the lowest point in the State.
Points of Interest in West Virginia
FAIRFAX STONE — Near Thomas, Tucker County. Marks head of No’rth Branch of Potomac. Was southern and western limit of the lands of Lord Fairfax. Near State Route No. 5 8.
SPENCER—Center of oil, gas, farming and stock-raising territory. Has one of State hospitals for insane. In Roane County at intersection of State Routes No. 14 (Temporary U. S. 21), No. 5, and No. 36.
BUCKHANNON—Home of West Virginia Wesleyan College.. Center of fine farming section. In Upshur County. At intersection of State Routes No. 5 and No. 22. "
WESTON—One of the State hospitals foi the insane is located here. Large glass plants. Also in fine agricultural country. At intersection of U. S. Highway No. 19 and State Route No. 5.
LEWISBURG—Center of a region that saw innumerable Indian struggles and many clashes during Civil War. Stone, church built in 1796 still in use. Many historic associations and is in magnificent scenic region. Center of blue grass stock farms. Site of old Fort Union. In Greenbrier County. At intersection of U. S. Highway No. 60 and State Route No. 24.
REYMANN MEMORIAL FARMS—A magnificent tract near Wardensville, Hardy County, presented to the State by the Reymann family of Wheeling, for experimental purposes. Near State Route No. 23.
NEW RIVER COAL FIELD—The New River Field is a part of the great West Virginia Smokeless Low Volatile Coal Area in the heart of the Appalachian Coal Field, located in Fayette and Raleigh Counties, West Virginia, and represents the pioneer coal development in the West Virginia Smokeless-Coal Fields. There is mined coal from the Fire Creek, Beckley and Sewell Seams, known throughout the world for its high carbon content, low ash content and freedom from impurities and its high British Thermal Units, making a superior fuel for steam, by-product and domestic purposes. The New River Field is traversed on the north by the famous Midland Trail and to the south by the Lakes to Florida Highway, which passes right through the center of this great coal field. In the New River Coal Field is found nature’s most beautiful handiwork in the famous New River Canyon, Hawks Nest Rock, Grand View, Stonehouse, used as a hospital in Civil War days and as a temporary residence of George Washington in the early pioneer days, and in addition shaft mines from 500 to 600 feet deep, slope mines and drift mines.

Points of Interest in West Virginia
WHEELING—Manufacturing metropolis of the State. Steel, iron, glass, pottery, stogies, and a wide variety of other products. State of West Virginia was formed here and city was the first capital. Has largest proprietary remedies company in the world. Many historic points, including site of old Fort Henry, associated with daring exploit of Elizabeth Zane, and McColloch’s Leap, where bold scout of pioneer days escaped from Indians. On Ohio river, in Ohio County, at intersection of U. S. No. 40, (National Road) and State Route No. 2.
WELLSBURG—Point of origin of Grimes Golden apple. Manufacturing town. At intersection of State Routes No. 2 and No. 27. In Brooke County, on Ohio river.
NEWELL, CHESTER and NEW CUMBERLAND •—Manufacturing towns in Hancock County, noted for pottery. State Route No. 2. Chester is at intersection of Route No. 2 and U. S. Highway No. 30 (Lincoln Highway).
PARKERSBURG—Progressive manufacturing city. Mammoth artificial silk plant; only Vitrolite plant in the world, great shovel plant, oil well machinery plant and many others. On Ohio river in Wood County, at intersection of U. S. No. 21, U. S. No. 50. and State Route No. 2.
MOUNDSVILLE—Takes name from largest prehistoric mound of its kind in America. State penitentiary located here. Manufacturing town, on Ohio river, at intersection of State Routes No. 2 and No. 6.
FOLLANSBEE and WEIRTON—Important steel and iron manufacturing points on State Route No. 2, north of Wellsburg.
MANNINGTON—Progressive manufacturing city in Marion County on State Route No. 6.

Points of Interest in West Virginia
BLUEFIELD—West Va.-Va., on the State line. Is the highest city in either of the Virginias, the altitude at the Municipal Building on the West Virginia side being 2612 feet above sea level. Bluefield’s delightful summer temperature averages a drop of 25 to 30 degrees at night, making blankets necessary every night of the year. The population of the two Blue-fields is 25,000, all but 5,000 of which are in West Virginia. The city is the metropolis and distributing center for the great Pocahontas coal fields. U. S. Highway No. 19 (from Tallahassee, Atlanta and Asheville) and U. S. 21 (from Charlotte and Wytheville) converge at Bluefield. U. S. 21 reaches its highest elevation two miles south of Bluefield at South Gate, on the State line. An impressive long distance view into both States can be had at this point. Pinnacle Rock is a commanding eminence eight miles out from Bluefield on State Route No. 8.
THE POCAHONTAS COAL FIELD—The Pocahontas Coal Field is a part of the Great Appalachian Coal Field and comprises an area of about 225,000 acres in Tazewell County, Virginia, and Mercer and McDowell Counties, West Virginia, in which is mined the Nos. 3 and 4 Pocahontas Seams of semi-bituminous coal known throughout the world for their purity and high commercial value for steam, by-product and domestic purposes. It is traversed throughout by hard surfaced roads, State Route No. 8 passing through the center of the field from Bluefield to Welch. A Lakes-to-Florida Highway will also pass through the field over State Route No. 8 when completed from Huntington to Bluefield.
GRAND VIEW—Northeast of Beckley in Raleigh County. Considered one of the most magnificent views in the State. Includes view of part of New River Gorge. Reached by county road from U. S. No. 19-21.
NEW RIVER GORGE—One of the outstanding scenic attractions of West Virginia. Splendid views are obtained from U. S. No. 60 for a distance of several miles. One of the favorite views is from “Hawk’s Nest.” In Fayette County.

Registration Fees
Automobiles of two thousand pounds or less, thirteen dollars for calendar year. Sixty cents for each additional 100 pounds. Three-quarters, one-half, and quarterly fees accepted at corresponding calendar periods. For the last quarter an additional charge of one dollar is made.
Plates cannot be used after midnight of December 31, of the year for which issued.
Plates for the new year may be used ten days before January 1.
Registration card must be carried on car.
Operators
Every operator of a motor vehicle must be 14 years old or more. Fee for operator’s license, one dollar, good until revoked for violation of law or other sufficient cause. License card must be carried on car.
Chauffeurs must be 14 years old or more. Fee three dollars a year. Half fee after August 1. License may be revoked for violation of law or other sufficient cause. License card must be carried on car.
Speed Limits
Speed limits for automobiles on open country highways, 35 miles per hour. On suburban street, 25 miles per hour. On city street, 15 miles per hour.
Accidents
The law requires that in case of accident, the operator stop his car immediately, give his name, address, and the number of his license, and render such assistance as may be reasonable or necessary.
In case of injury to any person, the operator shall report the details to the State Road Commission, Charleston, W. Va.
Penalty for violation, fine of not less than twenty-five nor more than one hundred dollars. Penalty for failure to stop after serious injury of any person, fine of not less than one hundred nor more than one thousand dollars, or imprisonment of not less than thirty days nor more than one year.
Driving While Intoxicated
For the first offense of driving while intoxicated or under the influence of narcotics, the penalty is a fine of not less than twenty-five nor more than one hundred dollars, and imprisonment of not less than sixty days nor more than six months. The second offense is a felony, punishable by not less than one and not more than three years in the penitentiary.
Lights
Headlights must be so designed and mounted as to prevent glare.
Red light required on rear of car, on left side. Rear plate must be illuminated at night with a white light
Right of Way
J he driver of a motor vehicle has the right of way over another driver approaching from the left at an intersection. He must give the right of way to another driver approaching from the right at an intersection.

MILEAGE CHART
This chart shows distances between principal points in West Virginia. The distances are based upon surveyed mileage from corporate limits to corporate limits via the shortest orthe most practicable route, plus a reasonable distance within the larger cities and towns.
HOW TO USE THE CHART - The mileage between any two points is shown at the intersection of the horizontal line leading from left to right from one of the points, with the vertical line leading downward from the other.
For instance, to find the distance from Alderson to Chester, follow the line leading to the right from Alderson until it intersects the line leading down from Chester. The figure in the square is 334, which is the mileage between the two points.

Points of Interest in West Virginia
HARPERS FERRY—Scene of John Brown’s attempt to free the slaves. Meeting place of Potomac and Shenandoah rivers. Spectacular scenery. In Jefferson County, on State Route No. 50.
CHARLES TOWN—Where John Brown was tried and hanged. Also former home of several relatives of George Washington. In Jefferson County, at intersection of State Routes No. 49 and No. 50.
SHEPHERDSTOWN—Oldest town in West Virginia. Where James Rumsey invented the first steamboat and tested it on the Potomac. In Jefferson County, on State Route No. 48.
MARTINSBURG—Chief city of the great West Virginia fruit region and home of nationally-known knitting mills. In Berkeley County, at intersection of U. S. Highway No. 11, and State Routes No. 47 and No. 49. .
BERKELEY SPRINGS—State park here contains springs with remarkable medicinal powers, gift of Lord Fairfax to Colony of Virginia. Central point of agricultural region producing especially fine tomatoes. In Morgan County at intersection of State Routes No. 9 and No. 47.
POINT PLEASANT — Scene of historic battle Oct. 10, 1774. Commemorated by towering monument and State park. Old Indian smoke signal point near by. Indian Chief Cornstalk, and “Mad Anne” Bailey, heroine of pioneer days, buried here. On the Ohio, at mouth of the Great Kanawha. One of finest river views in State. In Mason County. At intersection of State Routes No. 19 and No. 62.
MARLINTON—Many historic associations. Site of old Fort Greenbrier. General Lee said to have spent first night under canvas here at beginning of Civil War. Associated with many bloody fights between Indians and settlers. Old Warrior’s Road, an Indian trail, may still be plainly seen. Magnificent scenic region. At intersection of State Routes No. 24 and No. 43 in Pocahontas County. (No. 24 is Seneca Trail.)
BLENNERHASSETT ISLAND—In the Ohio river, within sight of Parkersburg. Where Aaron Burr plotted to form a Southwestern empire.

CLARKSBURG—Important manufacturing and commercial city. Birthplace of “Stonewall’’ Jackson. Center of large coal and chemical industries. In Harrison County, at intersection of U S. 50, U. S. 19, and State No. 22.
CHEAT RIVER REGION—In Monongalia, Preston, and Tucker Counties. Highlands and gorges, forests and rushing waters. Profusion of scenic views. Reached over U. S. No. 50, State Route No. 7, and their tributary roads.
MORGANTOWN—Home of West Virginia University. Half-million-dollar stadium seating 32,000 recently completed. Progressive manufacturing city. In Monongalia County at intersection of U. S. 19, U. S. 119, State Route No. 7, and State Route No. 73.
FAIRMONT—Vigorous manufacturing city. A central point in big Monongahela Valley coal field. At intersection or U. S. No. 19, State Route No. 6 and State No. 73. In Marion County.
FALLS OF TYGART VALLEY RIVER—Between Fairmont and Grafton. Series of cascades and rapids a mile in length. Near State Route No. 6.
GRAFTON—Important railroad town. Has State’s only National soldiers’ cemetery. Childhood home of Anna Jarvis, founder of Mother’s Day. In Taylor County, at intersection of U. S. 50 and State No. 56.
PHILIPPI—Home of Broaddus College. Scene of first inland battle of Civil War. In Barbour County at intersection of State Routes No. 56 and No. 69.
STATE FOUR-H CAMP—At Jackson’s Mill, the boyhood home of “Stonewall” Jackson, to whom It is a memorial. Maintained by the State as a training school for farm boys and girls, in all the various phases of farm life, and in all the things that go to make good citizens. Open all the year. In Lewis County, a few miles north of Weston, reached via U. S. 19 and paved county road.
STATE GAME FARM—A preserve for native wild animals. In Upshur County. On State Route No. 22, just south of French Creek.
WEBSTER SPRINGS—Scenic summer resort. In midst of spectacular mountains and forests. In Webster County, at intersection of State Routes 15 and 22.
ELKINS—Home of Davis and Elkins College. Beautifully situated. In Randolph County, at intersection of State Routes No. 53, No. 56, and No. 5 8. In good lumber, coal, and cattle territory.
BIRTHPLACE OF ABRAHAM LINCOLN’S MOTHER—It has been definitely established that Nancy Hanks was born near Burlington, Mineral County, West Virginia. On U. S. Highway No. 50.
CHARLESTON—Capital city of West Virginia. Beautifully situated modern metropolis. Manufacturing and commercial center. Chief city of world’s greatest bituminous coal region. Mammoth axe and sheet glass factories. U. S. Government armor plate plant. Chemical plants of DuPont interests and numerous others. In Kanawha County. At intersection of U. S. No. 60, U. S. No. 21, State Route No. 2 and State Route No. 19.
STATE MUSEUM AT CHARLESTON (in City Library Building, Lee Street). Some of the more important objects of interest:
Large collection of Indian implements; relics of pioneer times; relics of all our wars; Civil and World War	flags; a	Daniel Boone	collection;	the rifle of
Lewis Wetzel, the Indian scout; the desk of John Beckley, first Clerk of the Continental Congress, at which some of the signers of the Declaration of Independence are said to have affixed their signatures to that immortal document; a model of Rumsey’s steamboat, and a model of the Blennerhassett Mansion.
WORLD’S	GREATEST	BITUMINOUS COAL
FIELD—Along and south of U. S. No. 60 in West V irginia lie the most extensive deposits of bituminous coal	on earth. Much of	it is the	high grade
smokeless coal. The total is estimated to be sufficient, at the present rate of production, to last 2,000 years, and is valued at six hundred billion dollars. Greater part of this land was once owned by Robert Morris, who	financed	the American	Revolution.	Penetrated
by several roads branching off from U. S. No. 60. Chief city next to Charleston is Bluefield. Important cities and towns include Beckley, Logan, Welch, Williamson, Hinton, Princeton, Fayetteville, Pineville, Wayne, Madison, Hamlin, Matoaka, Northfork, Kimball, Oak Hill. Mt. Hope, Montgomery, Whitesville, Mullens, Sharpies, Glen Rogers, Eccles, and scores of others.
SOUTH BRANCH OF POTOMAC and NATIONAL PARKS REGION—This great scenic area includes portions of several counties in the northeastern part of the State. With more than 400 miles of trout streams, an abundance of wild game, and innumerable ideal camping spots, all in the midst of magnificent mountain scenery, it forms a veritable paradise for the vacationist or the sportsman. Almost all of the Monongahela National Forest lies in West Virginia, covering parts of Tucker, Randolph, Grant, Pocahontas, and Pendleton Counties. A part of the Shenandoah National Forest lies in Hardy, Pendleton, and Hampshire counties, extending eastward into Virginia These forests are guarded by Government rangers, lookouts, and patrolmen. There is an excellent system of forest trails connecting with State roads, and telephone communication is readily available.
No permit is required for a temporary camp in a National Forest. All campers are required to be careful about fire. The State laws apply to hunting and fishing, and may be obtained from the State Game and Fish Commission, Charleston, W. Va.
The main road penetrating this region is State Route No. 28, hard surfaced all the way from its intersection with U. S. 50, through Hampshire, Hardy, Grant, and Pendleton Counties, to Franklin. It has numerous tributary roads which are excellent in summer and fall.
A few of the many features of the region are:
East Seneca Ridge, including “Seneca Rocks,” and Miley Gap—a vertical stratum of quartzite of flinty hardness, extending across part of Grant and all of Pendleton County. Where visible, the top is seen against the sky line like a notched knife blade. The beautiful cliffs known as “Seneca Rocks” are on the North Fork, at the mouth of Seneca Creek, along State Route No. 53, in Pendleton County. Four miles below is seen Miley Gap, where two parallel sheets of quartzite rise vertically like a slender spire 600 feet toward the sky. The varied coloring of the quartzite adds greatly to its attractiveness.
“Smoke Hole” is a canoe-shaped valley north of Upper Tract in Pendleton County, through which flows the South Branch. It is conveniently reached from State Route No. 28.
MOUNT HOPE—West Va., situated midway between Charleston and Bluefield, on the Lakes to Florida Highway, founded 1 889, destroyed by fire March 24, 1910, presents one of the most thriving little cities in the State of West Virginia. Population about 5000. Altitude approximately 1900 feet. Good schools, all main thoroughfares paved, modern and well equipped paid fire department, good churches, and the heart and distributing center of the New River Coal Fields. Sulphur water of medicinal quality is found in abundance.
HUNTINGTON—One of State's largest cities, and one of chief manufacturing and commercial centers. Has 156 manufacturing plants, making wide variety of products of steel, glass, nickel, and wood. Railroad gateway for millions of tons of coal. Big tobacco market. New million dollar bridge spans Ohio river connecting roads of West Virginia and Ohio. At intersection of U. S. No. 60, U. S. No. 52, and State Routes No. 8, No 10, and No. 62.
ICE MOUNTAIN—A natural refrigerator containing ice even on the hottest days. This phenomenon is in the eastern part of Hampshire County, about half a mile from North River Mills. At the base of a mountain along North River, for a space 200 yards long and 35 feet wide, ice in large quantities is found throughout the year. It lies between U. S. 50 and State Route No. 9.
ORGAN CAVE—Large cave with passageways improved and lighted for about a mile. Used by Confederate forces for manufacture of saltpetre during war. Takes name from organ pipe formation of stalactites. Many other interesting formations. In Greenbrier County, near boundary of Monroe County. Near State Route No. 24.
WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS—Nationally famous resort for more than one hundred years. First summer White House still standing. A favorite spot of prominent men and women. Palatial hotels and wide variety of indoor and outdoor recreation. In Greenbrier County on U. S. No. 60.
CANAAN VALLEY and BLACKWATER FALLS —A magnificent valley lying in an oval, surrounded by a ridge of hills. The falls of the Blackwater river in this valley, are considered among the most beautiful in the state. In northeastern corner of Tucker County, reached from State Routes No. 58 and No. 40.
CAPON SPRINGS—Natural mineral springs with same analysis as those of Carlsbad. Visited by Daniel Webster, President Pierce and other noted men. In southeastern corner of Hampshire County, near State Route No. 23.
SPRUCE KNOB—Highest point in State. In southwestern corner of Pendleton County. It is 4.860 feet above sea level. Harper’s Ferry, 260 feet, is the lowest point in the State.
FAIRFAX STONE — Near Thomas, Tucker County. Marks head of North Branch of Potomac. Was southern and western limit of the lands of Lord Fairfax Near State Route No. 58.
SPENCER—Center of oil, gas, farming and stock-raising territory. . Has one of State hospitals for insane. In Roane County at intersection of State Routes No. 14 (Temporary U. S. 21), No. 5, and No. 36.
BUCKHANNON—Home of West Virginia Wesleyan College. Center of fine farming section. In Upshur County. At intersection of State Routes No. 5 and No. 22.
WESTON—One of the State hospitals for the insane is located here. Large glass plants. Also in fine agricultural country. At intersection of U. S. Highway No. 19 and State Route No. 5.
LEWISBURG—Center of a region that saw innumerable Indian struggles and many clashes during Civil War. Stone church built in 1796 still in use. Many historic associations and is in magnificent scenic region. Center of blue grass stock farms. Site of old Fort Union. In Greenbrier County. At intersection of U. S. Highway No. 60 and State Route No. 24.
REYMANN MEMORIAL FARMS—A magnificent tract near Wardensville, Hardy County, presented to the State by the Reymann family of Wheeling, for experimental purposes. Near State Route No. 23.
NEW RIVER COAL FIELD—The New River Field is a part of the great West Virginia Smokeless Low Volatile Coal Area in the heart of the Appalachian Coal Field, located in Fayette and Raleigh Counties, West Virginia, and represents the pioneer coal development in the West Virginia Smokeless Coal Fields. There is mined coal from the Fire Creek, Beckley and Sewell Seams, known throughout the world for its high carbon content, low ash content and freedom from impurities and its high British Thermal Units, making a superior fuel for steam, by-product and domestic purposes. The New River Field is traversed on the north by the famous Midland Trail and to the south by the Lakes to Florida Highway, which passes right through the center of this great coal field. In the New River Coal Field is found nature’s most beautiful handiwork in the famous New River Canyon, Hawks Nest Rock, Grand View-, Stonehouse, used as a hospital in Civil War days and as a temporary residence of George Washington in the early pioneer days, and in addition shaft mines from 500 to 600 feet deep, slope mines and drift mines.

Points of Interest in West Virginia
WHEELING—Manufacturing metropolis of the State. Steel, iron, glass, pottery, stogies, and a wide variety of other products. State of West Virginia was formed here and city was the first capital. Has largest proprietary remedies company in the world. Many historic points, including site of old Fort Henry, associated with daring exploit of Elizabeth Zane, and McColloch’s Leap, where bold scout of pioneer days escaped from Indians. On Ohio river, in Ohio County, at intersection of U. S. No. 40, (National Road) and State Route No. 2.
WELLSBURG—Point of origin of Grimes Golden apple. Manufacturing town. At intersection of State Routes No. 2 and No. 27. In Brooke County, on Ohio river.
NEWELL, CHESTER and NEW CUMBERLAND —Manufacturing towns in Hancock County, noted for pottery. State Route No. 2. Chester is at intersection of Route No. 2 and U. S. Highway No. 30 (Lincoln Highway).
PARKERSBURG—Progressive manufacturing city. Mammoth artificial silk plant, only Vitrolite plant in the world, great shovel plant, oil well machinery plant and many others. On Ohio river in Wood County, at intersection of U. S. No. 21, U. S. No. 50. and State Route No. 2.
MOUNDSVILLE—Takes name from largest prehistoric mound of its kind in America. State penitentiary located here. Manufacturing town, on Ohio river, at intersection of State Routes No. 2 and No. 6.
FOLLANSBEE and WEIRTON—Important steel and iron manufacturing points on State Route No. 2, north of Wellsburg.
MANNINGTON—Progressive manufacturing city in Marion County on State Route No. 6.

Points of Interest in West Virginia
BLUEFIELD—West Va.-Va., on the State line. Is the highest city in cither of the Virginias, the altitude at the Municipal Building on the West Virginia side being 2612 feet above sea level. Bluefield’s delightful summer temperature averages a drop of 25 to 30 degrees at night, making blankets necessary every night of the year. The population of the two Blue-fields is 25,000, all but 5,000 of which are in West Virginia. The city is the metropolis and distributing center for the great Pocahontas coal fields. U. S. Highway No. 19 (from Tallahassee, Atlanta and Asheville) and U. S. 21 (from Charlotte and Wytheville) converge at Bluefield. U. S. 21 reaches its highest elevation two miles south of Bluefield at South Gate, on the State line. An impressive long distance view into both States can be had at this point. Pinnacle Rock is a commanding eminence eight miles out from Bluefield on State Route No. 8.
THE POCAHONTAS COAL FIELD—The Pocahontas Coal Field is a part of the Great Appalachian Coal Field and comprises an area of about 225,000 acres in Tazewell County, Virginia, and Mercer and McDowell Counties, West Virginia, in which is mined the Nos. 3 and 4 Pocahontas Seams of semi-bituminous coal known throughout the world for their purity and high commercial value for steam, by-product and domestic purposes. It is traversed throughout by hard surfaced roads, State Route No. 8 passing through the center of the field from Bluefield to Welch. A Lakes-to-Florida Highway will also pass through the field over State Route No. 8 when completed from Huntington to Bluefield.
GRAND VIEW—Northeast of Beckley in Raleigh County. Considered one of the most magnificent views in the State. Includes view of part of New River Gorge. Reached by county road from U. S. No. 19-21.
NEW RIVER GORGE—One of the outstanding scenic attractions of West Virginia. Splendid views are obtained from U. S. No. 60 for a distance of several miles. One of the favorite views is from “Hawk's Nest.” In Fayette County.

Registration Fees
Automobiles of two thousand pounds or less, thirteen dollars for calendar year. Sixty cents for each additional 100 pounds. Three-quarters, one-half, and quarterly fees accepted at corresponding calendar periods. For the last quarter an additional charge of one dollar is made.
Plates cannot be used after midnight of December 31, of the year for which issued.
Plates for the new year may be used ten days before January 1.
Registration card must be carried on car.
Operators
Every operator of a motor vehicle must be 14 years old or more. Fee for operator’s license, one dollar, good until revoked for violation of law or other sufficient cause. License card must be carried on car.
Chauffeurs must be 14 years old or more. Fee three dollars a year. Half fee after August 1. License may be revoked for violation of law or other sufficient cause. License card must be carried on car.
Speed Limits
Speed limits for automobiles on open country highways. 35 miles per hour. On suburban street, 25 miles per hour. On city street, 15 miles per hour.
Accidents
The law requires that in case of accident, the operator stop his car immediately, give his name, address, and the number of his license, and render such assistance as may be reasonable or necessary.
In case of injury to any person, the operator shall report the details to the State Road Commission, Charleston, W. Va.
Penalty for violation, fine of not less than twenty-five nor more than one hundred dollars. Penalty for failure to stop after serious injury of any person, fine of not less than one hundred nor more than one thousand dollars, or imprisonment of not less than thirty days nor more than one year.
Driving While Intoxicated
For the first offense of driving while intoxicated or under the influence of narcotics, the penalty is a fine of not less than twenty-five nor more than one hundred dollars, and imprisonment of not less than sixty days nor more than six months. The second offense is a felony, punishable by not less than one and not more than three years in the penitentiary.
Lights
Headlights must be so designed and mounted as to prevent glare.
Red light required on rear of car, on left side. Rear plate must be illuminated at night with a white light.
Right of Way
1 he driver of a motor vehicle has the right of way over another driver approaching from the left at an intersection. He must give the right of way to another driver approaching from the right at an intersection.

Forests have been created in the Appalachian Range
The Massanutten Range extends from Waterlick and Strasburg on the north in a southwesterly direction to McGaheysville and Keezletown, a distance of approximately 50 miles. In width the range averages about 3 miles for the southern half and 6 miles for the northern half.

Elizabeth Furnace may be reached from Waterlick
the nearest railroad point and post office 3 or 4
miles distant, by a wagon road. Strasburg, on the
famous Valley Pike, the nearest town of any size, is
4 mile west of Waterlick. Elizabeth Furnace may
also be reached by automobile, except in wet weather.
The mail from Dilbeck to Waterlick and return
passes Elizabeth Furnace daily, and the carrier Will *
deliver mail if a box is provided. There are two trains daily from Washington, arriving, respectively about noon and in the early evening.
A telephone line, connecting with the country store at Waterlick and with farm houses in the Fort

Lots may be
through the purchase by the Government of large areas of mountain land. The primary purpose in establishing these new Forests is to secure and to maintain a growth of forest on the watersheds of navigable streams, as one means of preventing floods, and checking the erosion of steep slopes and the silting up of river channels. At the same time, they afford every opportunity for recreation, and along with the National Forests in the West should serve as public playgrounds where everyone may find rest and enjoyment.
Visitors are welcome at all times. They may camp on Government land anywhere that the fancy strikes them, and are free to fish and hunt, subject only to the State game laws. Ail that is asked of pleasure seekers is to be careful with fire in the woods, to keep their camping places in sanitary condition, and to avoid polluting the streams. All roads and trails are well marked with signs, and local - Forest officers are glad to give advice and assistance to visitors.
The Massanutten National Forest lies in the Massanutten Mountains, in the eastern portion of Shenandoah and Rockingham Counties and the western portion of Warren and Page Counties, Virginia.

These lots are near beautiful Passage Creek, which supplies plenty of water for washing and bathing. The Furnace Spring, which bubbles out of a rock cliff close to the upper end of the site, supplies ample drinking water for a considerable colony, tion is such that water may, if required, be piped a distance of a mile through the grounds.
ACCESIBILITY.
?
The Massanutten Forest is perhaps the most accessible of all the eastern Forests to the large centers of population and is so near the cities of Washington and Baltimore that it is entirely practicable for visitors to spend week-ends throughout the summer seasons in the mountains and to take one or more of the delightful trips over the new trials built by the Forest Service.
Temporary camps may be located free of charge and without formal permit. Those who desire to build summer homes, hotels, and the like, may obtain a term * * permit covering a period not to exceed 30 years at an annual charge of not less than $10 for tracts not exceeding 5 acres in size.
Space prevents an extensive description of all the summer home sites in the Massanutten National Forest. Perhaps the two most attractive and most accessible locations are those at Elizabeth Furnace and at.Sorbuck, and these will be described.
THE MASSANUTTEN MOUNTAIN.
The Massanutten is made up of many mountains, a number of long, level crested, parallel ranges. The formation, however, is not monotonous, for these mountains break off unexpectedly at water gaps. They run sometimes singly, and sometimes in pairs at elevations of from 2,000 to 2,400 feet. Some of the higher peaks reach elevations of 3,000 feet. Two ridges often merge, like the sides of some mythical Norse viking’s gigantic boat, into a peak resembling an upturned prow. Alternate lateral ridges and hollows, with their varying lights and shadows, give the longest stretch of mountain ridge a freedom from monotony that is wonderfully pleasing to the eye.
On the western and northern border, the north fork of the Shenandoah River alternately loops its silvery bends in toward the base of the mountain and out again around the ends of the long ridges which extend like ribs from the central backbone out into

Signal Knob, from which can be obtained a wonderful panorama of the ic Vale of Shenandoah from Winchester to Woodstock, is within walking distance. Two-day walking trips from this point may be arranged up to Kennedy’s Peak and Opeeche, or the trips may be made in a day, if an automobile

where residents of Page County are said to have gathered to watch the battle of New Market in the valley far below where the famous charge was made by the cadets from the Virginia Military Institute. The night may be spent at New Market where good accommodations are available.
This trip may be made in a day by using an automobile to the foot of the peak. By foot it is a hard two-day trip. Lodging may be obtained at farm houses near the base of the peak. This route traverses the Fort Valley.
EDINBURG TO CALEDONIA SPRINGS.
A fair automobile road leads from Edinburg to the Edinburg Gap, a big pass in the mountain. From the gap an old haul road now used as a Government trail turns to the south and traverses the Little Fort Valley through a beautifully wooded country to the Moreland Gap, where it strikes the public road again. A side trip may be made up the little-used path to the top of South Mountain overlooking the Shenandoah Valley. If it is desired to make a one-day trip, the return may be made by way of the beautiful Mount Airy estate to Mount Jackson and then by train to Edinburg.
WATERLICK TO SIGNAL KNOB.
NEW MARKET TO PITTS SPRING.
A new trail leaving the Fort Road about 3J miles from Waterlick leads to Meenaugah, the highest peak in this section, and thence down to the better viewpoint at the end of Signal Knob. There is no shelter after leaving the Fort Road. It is considered a fairly good one-day’s trip for an experienced walker. Water should be carried if the weather is hot. Some of the finest scenery in the Massanutten is seen from this route.

MOUNTAIN TRIPS IN THE MASSANUTTEN.
The new trails built by the Forest Service have opened up beautiful and heretofore little known portions of the Massanutten Mountains. The visitor can now ride or walk almost at will through these mountains and enjoy to the utmost the scenic attractions of the region. The letters and numerals signify the location of the town on the map. Corresponding letters and numerals will be found in the margins of the map. The United States Geological Survey is making of the plains, hills, and mountains shown, but also a topographic map of the United States. This the elevations. The line of the sea-coast itself is a work has been in progress since 1882, and about one-iifth of the area of the country, including Alaska, has been mapped. The mapped areas are widely scattered, nearly every State being represented, as shown on the progress map accompanying each annual report of the Director.
This great map is being published in atlas sheets of convenient size, which are bounded by parallels and meridians. The four-cornered division of land corresponding to an atlas sheet is called a quadrangle (a word used as specifically as section is in the surveys of the public lands).
The sheets are of approximately the same size: the paper dimensions are 21f by 18-^ inches; the map occupies about 17^ inches of height and 11^
to 16 inches of width, the latter varying with course surround these, just as they surround hills, latitude. Three scales, however, are employed. Those small hollows known as sinks are usually The largest scale is 1:62,500, or very nearly one indicated by hachures, or short dashes, on the mile to one inch; i. e., one linear mile on the inside of the curve. Certain contours, usually ground is represented by one linear inch on the every fifth one, are accompanied by numbers map. This scale is used for the thickly settled stating elevation above sea-level. Many other or industrially important parts of the country, heights, instrumentally determined, are also given, For the.greater part of the country an inter- the number in each case being placed in close mediate scale of 1:125,000, or about two miles to proximity to the point to which it applies, one inch, is employed. A third and still smaller scale of 1:250,000, or about four miles to one inch, has been used in the desert regions of the far West. A few special maps on larger scales are made of limited areas in mining districts.
The sheets on the largest scale cover 15' of latitude by 15' of longitude; those on the intermediate scale, 30' of latitude by 30' of longitude; and those on the smallest scale, 1° of latitude by 1° of longitude.
The features shown on this map may, for convenience, be classed in three groups: (1) water, including seas, lakes, ponds, rivers and other streams, canals, swamps, etc.; (2) relief \ including mountains, hills, valleys, cliffs, etc.; (3) culture, i. e., the works of man, such as towns, cities, road, railroads, boundaries, etc. The conventional signs used for most of these features are shown and explained in the marginal columns herewith.
All water features are shown in blue, the smaller streams and canals in full blue lines, and the larger streams, lakes, and the sea by blue water-lining. Certain streams, however, which flow during only a part of the year, their beds being dry at other times, are shown, not by full lines, but by lines of dots. Ponds which are dry during a part of the year are shown by oblique parallel lines. Salt-water marshes are shown by horizontal ruling interspersed with tufts of blue, and fresh-water marshes and swamps by blue tufts with broken horizontal lines.
The land features of the relief, usually represented on maps by shading of some sort, with pen or brush, are here shown by contour lines in brown. Each contour passes through those points which have the same altitude. If one follows a contour on the ground one will go neither uphill nor downhill, but on a level.

The contour line at, say, 20 feet above sea-level is the line that would be the sea-coast if the sea were to rise or the land to sink 20 feet. Such a line runs back up the valleys and forward around the points of hills and spurs. On a gentle slope this contour line is far from the present coast line, while on a steep slope it is near it. Thus a succession of these contour lines far apart on the map indicates a gentle slope; if close together, a steep slope; and if they run together in one line, as if each contour were vertically under the one above it, they indicate a cliff. The sheets composing the topographic atlas are designated by the name of a principal town or of some prominent natural feature within the district, and the names of adjoining published sheets are printed on the margins. The sheets are sold at five cents each when fewer than 100 copies are purchased, but when they are ordered in lots of 100 or more copies, whether of the same sheet or of different sheets, the price is two cents each.
The topographic map is the base on which the facts of geology and the mineral resources of a quadrangle are represented. The topographic and geologic maps of any quadrangle are finally bound together, accompanied by a description of the district, to form a folio of the Geologic Atlas of the United States.
