\ THE COUNTRY AROUND CAMP GORDON.1
By F. E. Matthes.
Camp Gordon stands about 8 miles northeast of Atlanta, the capital of Georgia, in an attractive region of rolling farmland and woodland. Viewed from the roof of one of Atlanta’s skyscrapers the country round about has the appearance of a vast undulating plain that extends in all directions out to the very horizon. The sky line is nearly level, yet the landscape is pleasing, for many local sags and swells give diversity to the surface, and the ruddy tints of the soil in the plowed fields contrast brightly with the somber green of the forests of oak and hickory. Nor is the region altogether lacking in bolder features. As the eye sweeps over the horizon it is suddenly arrested by the sight of a solitary mountain—a mountain so singularly round and smooth of outline that, veiled in the haze of distance, it looks more like a dome built by the hand of man than like a mountain shaped by natural processes. Yet a mountain it certainly is, as every Atlantan can attest—a mountain composed of rock so exceptionally and wonderfully solid that it has become known, most appropriately, by the name Stone Mountain. It stands about 14 miles east-northeast of Atlanta and rises 650 feet above the level of the plain, or 1,686 feet above the level of the sea.
Sweeping on northward along the horizon, the eye encounters, in the north-northwest, the dim outlines of another isolated mountain, one of more ordinary aspect than the first, and, unlike it, covered with dense woods. This is Black Jack Mountain, which stands 16 miles from Atlanta and rises 500 feet above the plain or 1,500 feet above the sea. Its south.side is being used as a backing for an artillery range. Immediately west of it lies the town of Marietta.
A little farther west, again, looms a mountain with a double sum-mit, which at once impresses itself upon the observer as one of the most prominent and most readily recognized landmarks of the region. It is Kenesaw Mountain, famous as the scene of one of the hardest fought battles of the Civil War. It stands 700 feet above the plain and 1,800 feet above the sea and is 19 miles distant from Atlanta.
Still farther west one may discern the low top of Lost Mountain, which is the smallest of this group of detached knobs. It stands only 350 feet above the plain and 1,450 feet above the sea and is 23 miles distant from Atlanta.
The name of Kenesaw Mountain, as already indicated, carries with it memories of the Civil War. All the country immediately north west of Atlanta, indeed, is rich in associations with the long cam paign that ended July 28, 1864, in the capture of the city by the Union forces. General Joseph Johnston, who had been steadily pushed southeastward by General Sherman, quickly perceived the strategic importance of Kenesaw Mountain and, mounting his batteries on its crest, converted the lone peak into a citadel which the Union men found impregnable. The trenches and gun emplacements are visible to this day. It was only by the superior number of his forces that Sherman was able to outflank Johnston and to compel him to abandon the stronghold. Minor engagements followed near Marietta and at the crossing of Chattahoochee River, but the decisive battle of the campaign was fought on the banks of Peachtree Creek, which flows midway between Camp Gordon and Atlanta. Here Sherman defeated Hood, who had succeeded Johnston in command, and thereby opened the way to Atlanta.
The four isolated mountains just described are on most days the only heights visible from Atlanta, but on an exceptionally clear day there also loom up, far to the north, other mountains of much greater mass and height. These are the Appalachian Mountains, or, more specifically, the southern members of the Blue Ridge in northern Georgia. They are fully 50 miles distant, and they afford the only visible indications of a limit to the plain on which Atlanta stands.
The plain is, indeed, of vast extent. It embraces a broad belt of rolling country that stretches from eastern Alabama northeastward along the front of the Appalachian Mountains through Georgia, the Carolinas, Virginia, and beyond, its total length being more than a thousand miles. Its width near Atlanta is about 120 miles. Because of its position at the foot of the Appalachian Mountains it is referred to commonly as the Piedmont (“foot of the mountain”), or, more properly, as the Piedmont Plateau, for, if considered with reference to the valleys that are cut into it, it is a high plain that has the aspect of a level-topped upland or plateau. Along the base of the mountains it ranges in altitude from 1,000 to 1,500 feet, and, although it slopes gradually southeastward, even its outer margin, where it joins the seaward-sloping Coastal Plain, stands at altitudes between 400 and 600 feet. At Atlanta and Camp Gordon, which lie just west of the middle of the belt, its altitude is about 1,050 feet. It is to this relatively high altitude that Atlanta and Camp Gordon owe their salubrious climate.
To one viewing the plateau from a height the degree to which its surface is cut by valleys may not be readily apparent, but to one traveling over it the depth of the numerous ramifying valleys and the steepness of their slopes become impressive facts. Almost everywhere the land is rolling or hilly ; at their heads the valleys are perhaps only 50 feet deep, but farther down in their courses they become 100 and even 200 feet deep. The main rivers, such as the Chattahoochee, flow 250 to 300 feet below the general level of the upland. Most of the valley bottoms are narrow and do not afford easy routes of travel; hence many of the main wagon roads and railroads follow the strips of upland that form the divides.
The broken topography of the plateau is well portrayed by the brown contour lines of the map on the other side of this sheet. Each of these lines on the map represents a contour on the ground—that is, an imaginary line that maintains the same level throughout its course. Any one who should follow a contour actually marked out on the ground would go neither uphill nor downhill but in curves like those described by the terraces which the farmers about Atlanta and elsewhere in the South make in their plowed fields to prevent the rain water from washing away the soil.
The manner in which contour lines express the shape and height of hills and valleys is illustrated by the ideal landscape and corresponding contour map in figure 1. The contour lines are drawn to represent vertical intervals of 20 feet—that is to say, from each contour represented to the next higher there is an ascent of 20 feet.
The spacing of the contour lines, it will be seen, varies with the slope of the ground represented; where the slope represented is gentle the contour lines are far apart; where the slope is steep they are close together. Where the map shows a bluff or cliff several lines may merge into one.
1 Based on data furnished by S. W. McCallie, State geologist of Georgia, and J. E. Brantley and supplemented by field observations made by the writer.
On the Camp Gordon map the contour interval is 50 feet; in other words, from each contour to the next higher there is an ascent of 50 feet. Thus on the sides of the Chattahoochee Yalley, which on the map are shown with as many as five or six contour lines in a distance of a quarter of an inch, there is a rise of 250 to 300 feet in half a mile.
v\w/(/ill!! 11
Figure 1.—Ideal landscape and corresponding contour map.
The blank areas where the contour lines are half an inch to an inch apart, on the other hand, represent gently rolling parts of the plateau surface that vary in elevation less than 50 feet over distances of 1 to 2 miles.
The contour lines are closest together on the parts of the map that represent the slopes of the isolated mountains. The north side of Kenesaw Mountain, up which the Union forces made their fruitless charges, is shown to ascend 650 feet in half a mile, and the northeast face of Stone Mountain is shown to rise abruptly 750 feet in a little more than a quarter of a mile, the lower half being almost sheer.
What now may be the meaning of the vast southeastward-sloping plateau, of the narrow valleys that interrupt its surface, of the isolated mountains that stand out boldly above its general level % Let us consider first the plateau.
The even sky line of the plateau, which is the dominant line in any general view, reflects the character that the region possessed in a former geologic period. The country then stood at a much lower level than it does to-day and formed a nearly even plain that sloped gently down to the level of the sea. The coast line then followed what are now the southeastern and southern margins of the Piedmont Plateau, about 80 miles southeast of Atlanta, and the broad belt of lowland beyond, which now constitutes the Coastal Plain, still lay submerged beneath the ocean. The deep and narrow valleys that now interrupt the surface of the plateau had not yet been carved, and the streams wandered lazily seaward by roundabout courses in very broad and very shallow valleys. The general aspect which the region then had may be best pictured by imagining the present deeply incised valleys to be again filled level with the top of the plateau.
The present valleys were cut in a more recent period, when the eastern part of the continent, including the Piedmont belt, was broadly uplifted and the present Coastal Plain emerged from beneath the sea in the form of a gently sloping margin. By this elevation of the land the fall of the streams was greatly increased and their flow was correspondingly quickened. Forthwith they began to scour and excavate their channels, and thus in time they cut their valleys deeper and deeper into the plateau and gave it the elaborately carved appearance which it has to-day.
The uplift, however, consisted not merely of a vertical rise but involved a broad up-arching or doming of a considerable part of the Appalachian region, by which the Piedmont Plateau was tilted, so that its southeastward slope to the Atlantic Ocean and its southward slope to the Gulf of Mexico became appreciably steeper than they were before. The effect of this tilting on the streams was to cause
them to abandon in large measure their previously roundabout courses and to seek new paths more directly down the slope. Especially pronounced was this effect upon the streams draining into the Atlantic Ocean, and, accordingly, most of these streams in eastern Georgia and the Carolinas are now arranged parallel to one another almost with the regularity of streamlets flowing side by side down a sloping board.
In the neighborhood of Atlanta and Camp Gordon there are several of these southeastward-flowing streams, notably South River, which heads in the southern and southeastern suburbs of the city, and Yellow River, which passes a few miles east of Stone Mountain. Both are tributaries of Ocmulgee River, known in its lower course as Altamaha River, which empties into the Atlantic Ocean through Altamaha Sound. A few miles southwest of Atlanta is the head of the first large stream that follows the southward slope to the Gulf of Mexico. This is Flint River, whose head branch is known as Mud Creek.
The streams west and north of Atlanta, on the other hand, do not all conform to this simple arrangement. Chattahoochee River, the master stream of the region, has a southwesterly course obliquely down the southerly slope of the plateau. It trends almost at right angles to the southeastward-flowing streams and, curiously, extends northeastward past the heads of a large number of them. It receives but few tributaries of any notable length from the east. Peachtree Creek is the largest in the Atlanta district; the others are only a few miles long. Consequently the divide between the Chattahoochee and the southeastward-flowing streams is at no place far from the river, and at some places it is less than 2 miles distant.
The divide may be readily traced southwestward along the main line of the Southern Railway to Norcross, thence southward through Tucker to a point 2 miles northwest of Stone Mountain, and thence southwestwrard through Clarkston and Decatur to Atlanta. Beyond Atlanta it apparently continues southwestward, but it is no longer a divide, properly speaking, for Flint River, of which Mud Creek is the head, joins the Chattahoochee not far from the mouth of that river.
In the absence of a conspicuous ridge the fact that Atlanta really stands on a divide may at first not be readily apparent, yet one need but view the city from the summit of Stone Mountain and behold its tall office buildings silhouetted like monuments against the sky to realize that it is built on a low swrell from which the country drops away to the east and to the west.
| « The southwesterly course of the Chattahoochee is probably due to the guiding influence of southwestward-trending belts of rock. In this part of the Piedmont Plateau the rocks are arranged largely in long and narrow, nearly parallel belts or strips that trend prevailingly southwestward. Some of them, being more easily worn down
than others, became in the course of time the paths of streams and determined the location and the trend of the valleys. There is, indeed, good reason to believe that the Chattahoochee established its southwesterly course along belts of relatively soft rock long before the plateau was tilted, and that, being somewhat deeply intrenched, it has maintained this course in spite of the tilting. The Chattahoochee is therefore to be regarded as a much more ancient river than any of the southeastward-flowing rivers in the Atlanta district.
The guiding influence of belts of soft rock shows itself in the trends of other streams besides the Chattahoochee. In the region represented on this map it is revealed by the courses of a number of tributaries to the Chattahoochee—for instance, by the southwesterly course of Oily Creek, which heads south of Marietta, and the southwesterly or northeasterly courses of several other branches of Sweetwater Creek; by the southwesterly courses of Nancy Creek and North Fork of Peachtree Creek, the two streams between which Camp Gordon is situated, of Burnt Fork and other lesser branches of Peachtree Creek, as well as of Long Island Creek and the upper part of March Creek. In the area east of the Atlanta divide the influence of the rock belts apparently dies out; only a few scattered streams have courses evidently laid along such belts. Most noteworthy are Jackson Creek and Camp Creek, which flow northeastward into Yellow River.
There remains to be explained the origin of the isolated mountains that rise above the plateau. These should be conceived as the remnants of high and extensive mountain chains which once occupied most of the area of the present plateau but which in the course of ages have been worn away by the elements. The former existence of these ancient mountain chains, which were among the earliest mountains of the North American continent, is attested by the exceedingly complex arrangement of the rocks that compose the plateau and the detached knobs. Wherever these rocks are exposed to view, as in deep road and railroad cuts, they are found to be fractured and
Figure 2.—Stone Mountain viewed from the northeast.
mashed, evidently by mighty compressive forces that acted horizontally within the crust of the earth. Whatever individual rock beds or layers can still be recognized are upturned and meet the surface of the plateau at all angles. In them one beholds the roots, so to sj>eak, of huge archlike rock folds that once towered thousands of feet above the present surface and that were the inner structural elements of mountain ranges of great height. The general direction of the rock folds, and consequently of the mountain ranges, was southwesterly, and this fact accounts for the prevailing southwestward trend of the rock belts in the plateau.
The almost complete disappearance of these ancient mountains seems even more remarkable than the manner in which they were created, for it was brought about by the very slow action of such processes as the decay and crumbling of rocks, the splitting of rocks asunder by frost and thaw, the washing and gullying of slopes by rain water, the cutting of ravines and valleys by brooks and rivers, and the carrying away of the wuiste of the land by streams to the sea. Not all parts of the mountain region, however, were reduced at the same rate, for the rocks did not everywhere offer the same resistance to destruction. Very naturally the parts composed of the weaker rocks were worn down faster and were the first to be transformed to lowlands; the parts composed of the harder rocks long remained mountainous but at length were reduced to detached groups of mountains and isolated knobs. The four lone mountains visible from Atlanta—Lost Mountain, Kenesaw Mountain, Black Jack Mountain, and Stone Mountain—are surviving masses of this sort; they have remained standing by virtue of the extreme hardness of their rocks.
This simple explanation becomes more impressive when it is realized that steep-sided mountains are much more exposed to the destructive action of atmospheric agents than a gently undulating plain. On steep slopes the rain water carries away the soil at a rapid rate—as fast, in places, as the soil is being formed by the decay of the rock—and thus it tends to keep the rock but thinly covered or even bare. On level or gently sloping ground, on the other hand, the rain water runs off so slowly that it can transport but very little of the soil, which thus in time forms a thick protective covering.
There could be no greater contrast in regard to depth of soil than there is between the four mountains mentioned and the upland surface of the Piedmont Plateau. On the plateau the rate at which the rain water has for ages washed away the soil has been very slow— slower, in fact, than the rate at which the rock decays and crumbles into soil, and the plateau therefore now bears a remarkably deep soil. As one may see in road and railroad cuts, of which there are especially good examples in and about the military reservation, the soil has a depth ranging in general from 10 to 50 feet; in places it reaches a depth of more than 100 feet. Steam shovels usually suffice for digging such cuts; blasting is seldom needed. The digging of military trenches, similarly, meets with but few difficulties. The soil is a compact clayey or sandy loam that grades almost insensibly into the solid rock underneath. It remains standing a long time in vertical walls.
The soil on the four isolated mountains, on the contrary, is scanty, and in places there is none. The crest of Kenesaw Mountain consists of bare crags—natural bastions of which the Confederate soldiers took advantage when they fortified the mountain. Stone Mountain is almost wholly bare of soil and in that respect offers an extreme contrast to the plateau, which is deeply covered with soil.
In its baldness as well as its smoothly rounded shape Stone Mountain (fig. 2) presents characteristics so singular and so nearly unique as to deserve a few words of special explanation. As already stated, the mountain has the appearance of a dome that rises abruptly and without transitional slopes from the plateau. It is not, however, regular in shape; it is more than 2 miles long (northwestward) and only 1 mile wide (northeastward); and its southwest side is only moderately inclined, but its northeast side descends almost as sheer as a wall. Its domelike appearance is heightened by its baldness; except for a few groups of pine trees and some shrubs and tufts of grass that have found a roothold on its sides the only forms of vegetation it bears are minute lichens.
The rock of which it is composed is granite, a material which in a period far remote surged up from below in a molten state and invaded the rock folds of the ancient mountains. It is much harder and tougher than any of the surrounding rocks, but its strangest feature is that, unlike most rocks which have been subjected to mountain-building stresses, it is essentially free from those parallel and more or less regularly spaced cracks that are called “joints.” A few sparse, discontinuous partings of this sort are visible in its sides, but as a whole the mountain is really a single, undivided block, a gigantic monolith.
Now a rock mass of this sort weathers only at its outer surface; instead of breaking up into angular blocks, like rock masses that are traversed by joints, it casts off layers parallel to its surface. Rock layers of this sort may be seen on many parts of Stone Mountain. They measure from a few inches to several feet in thickness and on a huge scale resemble the concentric layers of an onion. The tendency of the rock to become detached in successive layers is utilized by quarrymen, who hasten the process by blastiug or by steam or air pressure.
The rounded shape of the mountain is undoubtedly the result of the long-continued casting off of rock layers, for the process tends to remove angularities and to produce more and more smoothly curving surfaces. The original outlines of the monolith probably were irregular and angular.
The general lack of vegetation on the mountain is obviously due to the scarcity of crevices in which plants of any sort can take root. Most of the trees on Stone Mountain stand in places where fragments of rock layers have accumulated. A few isolated trees are rooted in narrow fissures that traverse layers still in place.
The size of Stone Mountain, it should be added, by no means represents the total extent of the granite mass of which it forms a part, for that mass has an area of many square miles. A large part of it probably was traversed by joints and has been worn down to the level of the plateau.
Not far from Stone Mountain there are other large areas underlain by granitic rock. The most extensive of these is at Lithonia and also bears a low but typically rounded dome of solid rock. This is the hill marked on the map “Little Stone Mountain” but more commonly known as Pine Mountain. Like Stone Mountain it is being quarried for paving stone and curbing.

ROUTE No. 1
Jer8ey City to Trenton, Via, Newark, Elizabeth, Rahway,
Metuchen, New Brunswick and Hightstown. All hard surface
Eavement. From Jersey City to New Brunswick this route is incoln Highway and is to connect at Jersey Citv with the Hudson River Vehicular Tunnel, when work is completed in 1926.
ROUTE No. 2
Trenton to Camden, Via Bordentown, Fieldsboro, Roebling Burlington and Bridgeboro. Four mile section from Burlington to Bridgeboro to be under construction. All other sections hard surface pavement. This route is to connect with Camden-Phila-delphia Bridge when this project is completed in 1926.
ROUTE No. 3
Camden to Absecon, via Collingswood, Haddon Heights Berlin, Hammonton and Egg Harbor City. Concrete pavement full distance. This is the famous “White Horse Pike,” leading to Atlantic City. Between Berlin and Absecon this route to be widened. Traffic over route to be maintained during widening.
ROUTE No. 4
Rahway to Absecon, Via Perth Amboy, South Amboy,
Keyport, Middletown, Red Bank, Eatontowrt; Long Branch, As-bury Park, Point Pleasant, Lakewood, Toms River, Barnegat,
Tuckerton and New Gretna.
Road Sections under construction: Perth Amboy •— Detour over city streets. Lakewood-Toms River—Detour over gravel roads.
Bridges under construction: Sea Girt-Wreck Pond—Traffic being maintained. Sea Girt-Manasquan River—Detour over concrete and gravel roads. West Point Pleasant-Inland Waterway—Detour over gravel roads.
Approximately 35y2 miles of this route, extending from Toms River to a point below New Gretna is a gravel road. Entire remaining distance hard surface pavement.
ROUTE No. 5
Newark to Delaware Bridge at Delaware, via Irvington, Springfield, Madison, Morristown, Dover, Netcong, Budd Lake, Hackettstown and Buttzville. Under construction between Delaware and Belvidere; also between Ledgewood and Netcong.
ROUTE No. 6
Camden to Salem and Bridgeton, via Woodbury, Mullica Hill and Woods-town. Branch from Mullica Hill to Bridgeton, 22 miles, via Pole Tavern. Branch from Salem to Bridgeton, 16.8 miles, via Quinton and Shiloh. Under construction between Quinton and Bridgeton.
ROUTE No. 7
Hightstown to Asbury Park, via Freehold, Jerseyville and Hamilton. Under construction between the Golf Course west of Asbury Park and road to Colt’s Neck. Road is hard surfaced from Hightstown to Freehold; gravel portion from Freehold beyond Jer-seyville.
ROUTE No. 8
Montclair to New York State Line at Unionville, via Singac, Wayne,
Pompton Plains, Butler, Newfoundland, Stockholm, Franklin Furnace and Sussex. Under construction between Smith’s Mills and Charlottsburg, and between Charlottsburg and Newfoundland.
Paterson to Fort Lee Ferry, via Dundee Lake, Hacken sack and Ridgefield to Fort Lee Ferry at Edgewater.
Following sections are under construction:
Broad Avenue, Ridgefield.
Arcadian Way to Fort Lee Ferry.
Hackensack to Paterson.
THESE ARE THE MARKS TO LOOK FOR
HIGHWAY,
VROUTEv/
The traveler will find poles banded along each route indicating the directions of routes as follows:
Blue Bunded Pole indicates that road runs north and south.
Red Banded Pole indicates
that road runs east and west.
Yellow Banded Pole indicates diagonal course, southeast or north-west.
Brown Banded Pole indicates diagonal course, northeast or south-west.
ROUTE No. 11
Newark to Paterson, Via Belleville, Nutley and Passaic. Kingsland Avenue, Nutley and Washington Avenue, Belleville under construction.
ROUTE No. 12
Paterson to Phillipsburg, via Little Falls, Pine Brook. Parsippanny, Denville, thence over Route No. 5 to Hackettstown, thence via Washington and Broadway. Under construction between Hackettstown and Port Colden.
ROUTE No. 13
New Brunswick to Trenton, via Kingston, Princeton and Lawrenceville. Under construction between Princeton and Trenton. This route is Lincoln Highway from New Brunswick to Trenton.
ROUTE No. 14
Egg Harbor City to Cape May City, via Mays Landing, Tuckahoe and Cape May Court House Under construction between Tuckahoe and Seaville. Practically all good gravel road from Egg Harbor City to Seaville; concrete from Seaville to Cape May City.
Directionary Signs
Cautionary Sign
CROSS
ROUTE No. 15
Bridgeton to Route No, 14 at Rio Grande, via Millville, Port Elizabeth, Dennisville, Goshen, Dias Creek and Green Creek. Under construction, Main Street, Millville. Hard surfaced road from Bridgeton through Millville to Menantico Creek; gravel road to Rio Grande.
ROUTE No. 16
Morristown to Princeton, Via Van Doren’s Mills, Bernardsville, Far Hills, Bed-minster, Pluckemin, Somerville, South Somerville, Belle Meade and Harlingen.
Following sections under construction:
Bernardsville to Passaic River.
Passaic River to Morris Township Line.
South Somerville to Woods Tavern.
Harlingen Cutoff.
Bayard Lane, Princeton.
ROUTE No. 17
Hackensack to New York State Line at Suffern, via Maywood, Ridgewood and Ramsey.
ROUTE No. 18
Penns Grove to Atlantic City, Via Sharptown, Woodstown, Pole Tavern, Elmer, Malaga, Downstown, Mays Landing, and Pleasantville. Hard surfaced pavement between Penns Grove and Woodstown; gravel road between Woodstown and Downstown. Downstown to Atlantic City, hard surfaced This road is popularly known as the Harding Highway.
ROUTE No. 20
Westville to Millville, via Hurffville, Glassboro, Malaga and Vineland. Hard surfaced pavement, Westville to Glassboro. Gravel section, Glassboro to Millville. This road is popularly known as the Delsea Drive.
State Highway Route No. 16, Section 2 Mine Mt,
Road—Bedminster Corner, Somerset County
ROUTE No. 9
Elizabeth to Phillipsburg, via Westfield, Plainfield, Bound Brook, Somerville, White House, Clinton, West Portal and Bloomsbury.
Following sections under construction:
White House to North Branch. Lincoln Avenue to Plainfield. Plainfield to Westfield. Westfield to Lehigh Valley R. R.
State Highway Bridge, Route No. 16, Section 3 —Bedminster Corner—Pluckemin, Somerset County

My dear Sir:
This map will speak for itself. It is worth your careful study. When you visit Boston, if you desire the greatest comfort with the least expense, you will find Hotel Rex-ford all right. By studying this map you will see the central location of the hotel, its nearness to the Union Station, State House, Court House, theatres and business houses. In other words, it is apart of Beacon Hill. Of course what you want when you visit Boston is comfort and safety, and, if economy goes with it, that makes a combination that will.undoubtedly prove satisfactory. Therefore, when in town, “ TRY THE REXFORD’» and we will make special efforts to please you.
Keep the map for reference. If you can’t come, send your friends.
Respectfully yours,

Brooklyn, and walk up Adams or Fulton Street to the Brooklyn City Hall, whence he can walk, or ride car down Montague Street to the j ferry and cross to the foot of Wall Street, New York. This will give him an excellent idea of Brooklyn's beautiful and aristocratic “heights.'’
If he has begun his excursion reasonably early in the morning, the visitor ought to reach Wall Street before the close of business at 3 o'clock, and so see Wall and Broad Streets in full tide, and get a look at the stock exchanges from their public galleries. Then let him go on to Broadway, admire Trinity Church, visit the Equitable Building and its roof, and stroll down to the Battery, where the harbor can be seen and a good idea obtained of the commercial importance of the city. That done, take a Broadway car up the great thoroughfare to the hotel, at Nos. 667-677.
The next day's time may properly be devoted to Central Park and the museums there. One may go up by the Broadway surface cars to the Seventh Avenue entrance, or by the Sixth Avenue Elevated Railway to the Sixth Avenue gate ; but a pleasant way is to walk over to Washington Square, five minutes from the hotel, and take a seat upon the roof of a Fifth Avenue stage. From this vantage-point, the whole of that grandest of American thoroughfares will pass, before your eyes. You may stop at the Plaza_ ^ or main entrance to the park, at Fifth Avenue and Fifty-ninth Street, or ride up to the Eighty- ^ second Street entrance and the Art Museum.
The former course is preferable. It is only a' few steps from the Plaza to the Menagerie, and thence you can wander on to the Mall and it statues, the Esplanade, the Ramble, and Belvi-oBti^ dere, and so on to the Art or Natural History museums.If you prefer to ride, and do not care to
hire a cab, take a seat in one of the public park phaetons, and ride the round of the drives; the fare is 25 cents for
the whole trip, and stop-over checks will be given at points of interest, as the obelisk and elsewhere. The best of people take advantage of these cheap and comfortable carriages, and the ride is very enjoyable. Some time should be given to the Metropolitan Museum of Art, whose treasures are free to public inspection every day except Monday and Tuesday, when 25 cents is charged. Various special guides and catalogues, may be bought at the door, which will greatly assist the visitor, though the labeling is profuse and explicit. If you are ready to return to the hotel, walk one block west and take the Madison (Fourth) Avenue electric cars to Bond Street and the Bowery, opposite the Broadway Central; or walk over to Eighty-fourth Street station of the Third Avenue Elevated Railway and go down to Houston Street station, three blocks from the hotel. A good plan, however, is to finish the day by walking straight f across the park, visiting the beautiful scientific collections in the Museum of Natural History at Eighth Avenue and Seventy-eighth Street, and then going down to the hotel by the sixth Avenue Elevated Railway from Eighty-first Street to Bleecker, or the Subway from
Broadway and 79th Street to Bleecker Street.
If the visitor is interested in shipping and the harbor,
he will enjoy strolling along the East River front from the bridge to the Battery, and visit the new Aquarium at Castle Garden; if he has a fancy for ocean steamers, let him
11
RAL
saunter along the North River side. Many delightful excursions upon the water may be taken. Boats ply hourly in summer to Coney Island and Staten Island in one direction, and in the other to Fort Lee, up the Hudson, and len Island, up East River. These are easily accessible from the Broadway Central Hotel.
The Statue of Liberty is another point of pilgrimage
to strangers. A steamboat leaves the Battery every
p^'xhour for Bedloe's Island, upon which the statue
stands, and a return ticket costs only 25 cents. Entrance
to the statue is free, and you may climb up to the
5
balcony in Liberty's crown if you please. The landscape visible thence, in clear weather, is one of the most magnificent in America, and fully repays the exertion. A free boat runs frequently between the Battery and Ellis Island, where visitors may witness the landing arid registration of foreign immigrants—a most instructive and amusing sight.
Brooklyn contains much to interest the stranger, especially Prospect Park and Greenwood Cemetery. The former is best reached by electric cars from the bridge terminus. To Greenwood, the Fifth Avenue (Brooklyn) Ele-&vated Railway runs direct, and public carriages |make the rounds of the cemetery at a small fcharge.
Such are a few of the more prominent objects and places of interest in the Imperial City,
which covers not only the whole of Manhattan Island, which is 13 1-2 miles long, and 2 1-2 miles wide, but several squaremiles of territory north of the Harlem River, where are situated the Zoological and Botanical Gardens of Bronx Park, considered in some respects the most | magnificent in the world.
Many other points of interest suggest or present themselves. To all of them, equally, the Broadway Central Hotel stands as a sort of focus, and from no other single point in the city can all be reached so conveniently and expeditiously.
Safety and Comfort .
Among the many improvements made by Mr.
Haynes in his reconstruction of the Broadway Central Hotel, is an entire double system of fire patrol and electric gongs throughout the building. In addition to this, extra bells are placed over the head of every bed in the house.
The great parlors and grand halls and
stairways are of magnificent proportions.
6


TRANSPORTATION
One of the most important, and
sometimes the most expensive, things in a great city is the matter of transportation, getting about from one place to another. In this respect, no hotel in New York has the convenience of such a central location, together yor\ Clearing house. with the rapid and economical transfer to all points, equalled by the Broadway Central Hotel.
The new Broadway electric lines, with their branches and extensions, now cover all the great avenues ; the new Lexington Avenue line, coming down from Harlem on the east side of the Grand Central Railroad Station, brings passengers direct from 42nd Street to the door, while the Broadway line from the Battery to Central Park passes every fashionable store, theatre and attraction of the city. The new Columbus and Lenox Avenue lines take passengers clear up to Harlem River and High Bridge, while both the Third and Sixth Avenue Elevated Roads, one block in front and one in the rear, give every possible facility for reaching all suburban locations at the least j>ossible charge. The Cross-Town cars passing Broadway, both above and below the hotel, connect directly with every foreign and
coastwise steamer; all the ferries, Battery, and Brooklyn Bridge Trains and to the Bronx and New Williamsburg Bridge.
The Bleecker Street Station of the rapid transit subway is one block in front of the hotel.
Thus the Broadway Central Hotel will be found exceptionally well located for business,
sight-seeing, or pleasure.
Business men will realize the convenience of
being located in the great centre of business rather than spend twenty minutes coming down town in a crowded car in the morning.

\ the “Hendrick Hudson” is graceful and powerful. Length 400 feet. Four decks. Capacity 5,500
JOHN BURROUGHS, the naturalist of the Hudson Valiev} wrote: ‘‘The longer I live the more my mind dwells upon the beauty and the wonder of the world. I have cliniped its mountains, roamed its forests, sailed its water* * * * and always have beauty and joy waited uqon my goings and comings.”
Many Gf lls who wish to see and enjoy the glory of nature, feel as John Burroughs felt, that beauty and joy await us out in the open, in the temple of nature.
One may sail the waters of the Hudson, roam the forests that come down to the water’s edge, climb the mountains that border hard by, or the more distant Catskills, and there breathe the pure, invigorating air, ajld' always have beauty and joy await upon his “goings and comings.”
The Hudson is without a peer for natural beauty. As one sails up the river he beholds the grandeur of the Palisades; great vertical rocks 500 feet in height, stretching along the western shore for fifteen miles; on the opposite shore are towns, villages, stately mansions, green fields, and distant vistas of loveliness.
One sails through the Tappan Zee between Tarry town and Nyack, a region where ‘'Ghost Stories” abound, and
The “Alexander Hamilton,” a popular member of the fleet. Length 350 feet. Four decks. Capacity 4,050
where the believer in legends may see Rambout Van Damm rowing his light skiff perpetually in punishment for breaking an ancient Sabbath blue law.
Throughout the Hudson Valley a glamour of history and legend adds a rich, colorful background to the scene. From the day Hendrick Hudson’s Half Moon sailed up the river, in 1609, the region has had an eventful existence. Here white man and red vied for possession; battles of the Revolution were fought; a spy was captured and hanged; and Ichabod Crane fled before the Headless Horseman.
Stony Point with its lighthouse marks the heights scaled by "Mad” Anthony Wayne. At Indian Point, a noted meeting place of the red men, is now located the Day Line resort of 320 acres of lawn, woods, lake, farm and extensive athletic fields. Just beyond are hills of impressive size. Peekskill (founded by Jans Peek) nestles at their feet in a sharp bend of the river. The southern gateway to the Highlands of the Hudson is here.
Anthony’s Nose is on the right going up the river and on the left is Dunderberg, a tall mountain that breeds the storm, the lightning and the thunder, and at whose feet Captain Kidd, it was believed, buried his
r—
4'
The interior of the “Robert Fulton.” is in garden style. Length 347 feet. Four decks. Capacity 4,000
treasure. While passing through the Highlands one beholds Bear Mountain; Sugar Loaf; Old Bull Hill, which bellows back the storm and thunder bred at Dunderberg; a cup-shaped mountain "Where the moon looked down on 'Old Cro’ Nest’ and mellowed the shade on his shaggy breast;” and Storm King (formerly Boter Berg) recognized by the highway cut in its granite face 500 feet up from the water’s edge.
The castle-like buildings at West Point in the Highlands mark the site of the United States Military Academy. The map in this Travelogue shows the place where, in the time of the War for the Independence of the United States, a heavy iron chain was laid on pointed timbers and stretched across the river to prevent the British ships from sailing up the river.
Passing out through the northern gateway of the Highlands, one sees the city of Newburgh across the bay, and on the opposite shore Mount Beacon where, in Revolutionary Days, beacon fires were lighted that might be seen for miles around, to give the colonists warning of the movements of the British troops or ships.
Farther on, the boat passes under the great cantilever railroad bridge at Poughkeepsie, half way between
The “Chauncey M. Depew,” docked at Indian Point, the lovely private park of the Day Line

IMESHIM
The rocky splendor of the Palisades enhances the lower part of river
New York’s ever-soaring skyline is magnificent as seen from boat deck
The “De Witt Clinton,” a favorite with excursionists. Length 332 feet. Four decks. Capacity 5,000
New York and Albany. At Poughkeepsie is located Vassar College, a pioneer college for girls. Poughkeepsie is from an Indian word Apokeepsing (a safe harbor), for it was in a cove near the Day Line pier that an Indian maiden found a "safe harbor” during a feud between two warring Indian tribes.
More open reaches of the river are now entered. Millionaires’ estates and mansions extend along the shores and for a mile or more back from the river.
Presently along the skyline of the western hills, one traces "the Old Man of the Mountains” lying there on his back. He is the giant, Onteora, which the great Indian spirit, Manitou, ordered into a mountain changed, for the many red men slain. One traces the outline of Onteora’s forehead, nose, chin, neck, breast and up-bended knee.
Kingston Point, where the Day Boat lands, marks the farthest point up the Hudson reached by Colonel Vaughn of the British Army in 1777.
The Catskills are beyond, where, at the head of Kaaterskill Clove, Rip Van Winkle slept long and awoke to the happenings of twenty years.
The river now grows narrower. The banks are more
Storm King is one of the many promontories that stud the Hudson like rugged jewels
r
The “Albany” has endeared herself to thousands. Length 327 feet. Three decks. Capacity 3,000
gently sloping, for this is a farming country. The Day Line Dock at CatskiU is reached, then five miles beyond, the city of Hudson, which was once upon a time a whaling port where whaling vessels were fitted out. The banks of the river grow still closer. Swells from the boat wash the nearby shores. Islands are numerous. As the boat nears Castleton it passes under the New York Central Railroad bridge. Soon Albany, the Capital of the Empire State, comes into view. The drawbridge opens and the charming, restful trip comes to an end as the boat docks at the Day Line Pier.
This travelogue has taken us up the river. The trip is equally fascinating in the opposite direction.
Rising up in the Adirondacks on the side of Mount Tahawus, in a little lake poetically called "Tear of the Clouds,” joined by brooks and larger streams, the Hudson becomes a great navigable stream at Albany on whose waters ran the first commercially successful steamboat, the Clermont of Robert Fulton. The beauty of the Hudson is due to the great range of its geological history. The Hudson is a river of romance and of history. It has become famous through the poems of Bryant, Holmes, Halleck and Drake; through the stories of James Feni-
The mammoth Bear Mountain Bridge is almost dwarfed by its environment
Length 268 feet. Four decks. Capacity 3,000
more Cooper and Washington Irving; and the historical writings of Benson J. Lossing, Joel T. Headly, and others.
It is fitting that the most beautiful inland steamers of the world should ply the waters of the most beautiful river.
Travel is the greatest of teachers. It is the open "Book of Knowledge,” the Appian Way to intellectual understanding. It is Nature’s university. It teaches contentment, patience, tolerance; it elevates one spiritually.
All of this, and more, may be experienced on a Hudson River Day Line steamer. The Day Line steamers are equipped with every convenience: handsomely carpeted saloons, spacious open decks, glass enclosed observation rooms, private parlors for families or parties, writing rooms, dining service, luncheon rooms, salaried orchestras, beautiful oil paintings and handsome decorations. Both children and adults revel in the fresh, bracing air of the Hudson.
Passengers holding rail tickets reading from New York to Albany, or Albany to New York, may have them exchanged for steamer tickets at the Purser’s office.
West Point, romantic and charming since Revolutionary days, enchants the eye

YALE UNIVERSITY
Yale University, founded in 1701 by a group of Connecticut ministers as the *<Collegiate School/’ whose purpose was to fit young men for service “in Church & Civil State,” was first located in Killingworth, later in Saybrook, and in 1716 moved to New Haven. It was given the name of Yale College in 1718m recognition of gifts received from Elihu Yale, formerly Governor of Fort St. George, Madras, and a native of New England. Connecticut Hall, the oldest brick building, was completed in 1752, and is still used as a dormitory. The statue of Nathan Hale, Class of 1773, stands in front of Connecticut Hall.
In addition to the undergraduate schools, Yale College and the Sheffield Scientific School (1863), which are entered through the Freshman Year, the University now comprises the Graduate School, established in 1846, and seven professional schools. Three of these, the School of Medicine, the Divinity School, and the School of Law, celebrated their centennials in 1913, 1922, and 1924, respectively. The School of the Fine Arts was established in 1866, the School of Music in 1894, the School of Forestry in 1900, and the School of Nursing in 1923.

The University faculty numbers 525. There were 4,445 students enrolled as candidates for degrees in 1924-2 5, 2,995 in the undergraduate schools and 1,450 in the graduate and professional schools. The total number of buildings used by the University is 142.
UNIVERSITY BUILDINGS
The accompanying map shows the location of University buildings and of the central churches and public buildings. The map key arranged by city blocks and alphabetically will assist visitors in locating buildings.
Buildings of special interest include: Connecticut Hall (11 S), completed in 1752; the Old Library (11 G), erected in 1842-46; the Memorial Quadrangle (10), the gift of Mrs. Stephen V. Harkness, of New York City, in memory of her son, Charles W. Harkness (B.A. 1883); the Sterling Chemistry Laboratory (36 E), the largest chemical laboratory ever erected as a single unit, and the Sterling Hall of Medicine (2 B), erected from funds provided by the Trustees of the Estate of John W. Sterling (B.A. 1864); and the Peabody Museum of Natural History (36A).

PLACES OF HISTORICAL INTEREST
The Pierpont House. (The Faculty Club, zoN, 149 Elm Street.)
This site was deeded by the Town of New Haven to the Rev. James Pierpont, the principal founder of Yale College!, as a portion of his ministerial settlement on September 25, 1685. It remained the property of the Pierpont family for over 200 years until it was bought in September, 1900, by the Rev. Anson Phelps Stokes, University Secretary from 1899 to I921. It was sold by him to the University in July, 1921, and is now used as a Faculty Club.

The Noah Webster House. (S.S.S. dormitory, 24 G, southwest -orner of Temple and Grove Streets. )
The wooden portion of this house was built about 1825 by Noah Webster (B.A. Yale 1778), author of the American Dictionary of the English Language. It is now used as a dormitory for students in the Sheffield Scientific School.
Grove Strebt Cemetery (26).
Many famous people are buried here. A list showing the location of graves may be consulted at the University Secretary’s Office.
New Haven Green (12).
The Green, with its three churches, is a sixteen-acre space around \ hich the original settlement was made. It was planned as a market place and was used for two centuries as a pasture for cattle. A liberty pole was set up in 1774.
Trinity (12 A), Center (12 B), and North (now United, 12 C) churches were all completed about 1814.
* UNIVERSITY COLLECTIONS
The Trumbull Collection of Paintings of the American Revolution and the Jarves Collection of Early Italian Paintings, in the School of the Fine Arts, are open to the public without charge on week days, during term time, from 1 ;ooto4:oop.m.
The Memorial Collection of Autograph Letters and Engravings of Eminent Yale Men in Memorial Hall may be seen at any time. Admission to other collections in Memorial Hall, comprising the Morris Steinert Collection of Musical Instruments and the Rebecca Darlington Stoddard Collection of Greek and Italian Vases, may be obtained on week days by application at the office of the University Treasurer, Woodbridge Hall.
The Collection of Babylonian Tablets and other remains in Room 202, Osborn Zoological Laboratory, and Collections in the Peabody Museum of Natural History, are open to visitors during term time between 10:00 a.m. and 1 2:00 m. and 2:00 and 4:00 p.m., from Monday to Friday, inclusive.
These collections are open on Sundays from November 1 to May 1, from 2 :oo to :30 p.m.
AUTOMOBILE ROUTES
Automobile routes in Connecticut are indicated by yellow and black pole markings. Numerals are black on yellow background enclosed in black square with bands extending around the pole. The signs of the Automobile Club of New Haven (Headquarters: Hotel Taft) are also yellow and black; these guide the motorist within the city to the various main routes leading out of the city. Routes start from Chapel
course.
